# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: governor-of-virginia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 6, 2012.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent Democratic president Barack Obama and his running mate, incumbent vice president Joe Biden, were elected to a second term.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They defeated the Republican ticket of former Massachusetts governor Mitt Romney and Wisconsin congressman Paul Ryan.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama and Biden were re-nominated by their party without strong opposition in the way.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Meanwhile, the Republican Party experienced a competitive primary, with Romney consistently competitive in the polls and winning the support of many party leaders, but facing challenges from a number of more conservative contenders.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Romney secured his party's nomination in May, defeating former senator Rick Santorum, former speaker of the House and Georgia congressman Newt Gingrich, and Texas congressman Ron Paul, among other candidates.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The campaigns focused heavily on domestic issues, and debate centered largely around sound responses to the Great Recession along with long-term federal budget issues, the future of social insurance programs, and the Affordable Care Act.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Foreign policy was also discussed, including the end of the Iraq War in 2011, military spending, the Iranian nuclear program, and appropriate counteractions to terrorism.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Romney claimed Obama's domestic policies were ineffective and financially insolvent while Obama's campaign sought to characterize Romney as a plutocratic businessman who was out of touch with the average American.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The campaign was marked by a sharp rise in fundraising, including from nominally independent Super PACs.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama defeated Romney, winning 332 Electoral College votes and 51.1% of the popular vote to Romney's 206 electoral votes and 47.2% of the popular vote.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He became the third sitting president in a row (after Bill Clinton and George W.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama carried all 18 "blue wall" states and defeated Romney in crucial swing states that Republicans had previously won in 2000 and 2004, namely Colorado, Florida, Nevada, Ohio, and Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Despite his loss, Romney managed to flip Indiana, North Carolina, and Nebraska's 2nd congressional district from the 2008 election.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ultimately, Obama won eight of the nine main swing states, losing only North Carolina.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Florida, Georgia, Ohio, Tennessee, and West Virginia's state legislatures approved measures to shorten early voting periods.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Florida and Iowa barred all felons from voting.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kansas, South Carolina, Tennessee, Texas, and Wisconsin state legislatures passed laws requiring voters to have government-issued IDs before they could cast their ballots.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This meant typically that people without driver's licenses or passports had to gain new forms of ID.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Former president Bill Clinton denounced them, saying, "There has never been in my lifetime, since we got rid of the poll tax and all the Jim Crow burdens on voting, the determined effort to limit the franchise that we see today".
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He was referring to Jim Crow laws passed in southern states near the turn of the twentieth century that disenfranchised most blacks from voting and excluded them from the political process for more than six decades.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton said the moves would effectively disenfranchise core voter blocs that trend liberal, including college students, black people, and Latinos.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Obama campaign fought against the Ohio law, pushing for a petition and statewide referendum to repeal it in time for the 2012 election.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In addition, the Pennsylvania legislature proposed a plan to change its representation in the electoral college from the traditional winner-take-all model to a district-by-district model.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As the governorship and both houses of its legislature were Republican-controlled, the move was viewed by some as an attempt to reduce Democratic chances.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ultimately, they did not do it, leaving their winner take all format intact as of 2020.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With an incumbent president running for re-election against token opposition, the race for the Democratic nomination was largely uneventful.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The nomination process consisted of primaries and caucuses, held by the 50 states, as well as Guam, Puerto Rico, Washington, D.C., U.S.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Virgin Islands, American Samoa, and Democrats Abroad.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Additionally, high-ranking party members known as superdelegates each received one vote in the convention.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A few of the primary challengers surpassed the president's vote total in individual counties in several of the seven contested primaries, though none made a significant impact in the delegate count.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Running unopposed everywhere else, Obama cemented his status as the Democratic presumptive nominee on April 3, 2012, by securing the minimum number of pledged delegates needed to obtain the nomination.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The first debate took place on May 5, 2011, in Greenville, South Carolina, with businessman Herman Cain, former New Mexico governor Gary Johnson, Ron Paul, Tim Pawlenty, and former Pennsylvania senator Rick Santorum participating.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Another debate took place a month later, with Newt Gingrich, Mitt Romney, former Utah governor Jon Huntsman, and Minnesota congresswoman Michele Bachmann participating, and Gary Johnson excluded.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A total of thirteen debates were held before the Iowa caucuses.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The first major event of the campaign was the Ames Straw Poll, which took place in Iowa on August 13, 2011.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Michele Bachmann won the straw poll (this ultimately proved to be the acme of her campaign).
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Pawlenty withdrew from the race after a poor showing in the straw poll, as did Thaddeus McCotter, the only candidate among those who qualified for the ballot who was refused entrance into the debate.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It became clear at around this point in the nomination process that while Romney was considered to be the likely nominee by the Republican establishment, a large segment of the conservative primary electorate found him to be too moderate for their political views.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Perry did poorly in the debates, however, and Herman Cain and then Newt Gingrich came to the fore in October and November.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Due to a number of scandals, Cain withdrew just before the end of the year, after having ballot placement in several states.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Around the same time, Johnson, who had been able to get into only one other debate, withdrew to seek the Libertarian Party nomination.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] For the first time in modern Republican Party history, three different candidates won the first three state contests in January (the Iowa caucuses, the New Hampshire primary, and the South Carolina primary).
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The election of county delegates at the caucuses would eventually lead to Ron Paul earning 22 of the 28 Iowa delegates to the Republican National Convention.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Newt Gingrich won South Carolina by a surprisingly large margin, and Romney won only in New Hampshire.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A number of candidates dropped out at this point in the nomination process.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bachmann withdrew after finishing sixth in the Iowa caucuses, Huntsman withdrew after coming in third in New Hampshire, and Perry withdrew when polls showed him drawing low numbers in South Carolina.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Santorum, who had previously run an essentially one-state campaign in Iowa, was able to organize a national campaign after his surprising victory there.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He unexpectedly carried three states in a row on February 7 and overtook Romney in nationwide opinion polls, becoming the only candidate in the race to effectively challenge the notion that Romney was the inevitable nominee.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, Romney won all of the other contests between South Carolina and the Super Tuesday primaries, and regained his first-place status in nationwide opinion polls by the end of February.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Super Tuesday primaries took place on March 6.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Romney carried six states, Santorum carried three, and Gingrich won only in his home state of Georgia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Throughout the rest of March, 266 delegates were allocated in 12 events, including the territorial contests and the first local conventions that allocated delegates (Wyoming's county conventions).
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Santorum won Kansas and three Southern primaries, but he was unable to make any substantial gain on Romney, who became a formidable frontrunner after securing more than half of the delegates allocated in March.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After disappointing results in the April 24 primaries (finishing second in one state, third in three, and fourth in one), Gingrich dropped out on May 2 in a move that was seen as an effective end to the contest for the nomination.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After Gingrich's spokesman announced his upcoming withdrawal, the Republican National Committee declared Romney the party's presumptive nominee.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ron Paul officially remained in the race, but he stopped campaigning on May 14 to focus on state conventions.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On May 29, after winning the Texas primary, Romney had received a sufficient number of delegates to clinch the party's nomination with the inclusion of unpledged delegates.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After winning the June 5 primaries in California and several other states, Romney had received more than enough pledged delegates to clinch the nomination without counting unpledged delegates, making the June 26 Utah Primary, the last contest of the cycle, purely symbolic.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] CNN's final delegate estimate, released on July 27, 2012, put Romney at 1,462 pledged delegates and 62 unpledged delegates, for a total estimate of 1,524 delegates.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] No other candidate had unpledged delegates.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The delegate estimates for the other candidates were Santorum at 261 delegates, Paul at 154, Gingrich at 142, Bachmann at 1, Huntsman at 1, and all others at 0.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On August 28, 2012, delegates at the Republican National Convention officially named Romney the party's presidential nominee.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Romney formally accepted the delegates' nomination on August 30, 2012.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Four other parties nominated candidates that had ballot access or write-in access to at least 270 electoral votes, the minimum number of votes needed in the 2012 election to win the presidency through a majority of the electoral college.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Candidates in bold were on ballots representing 270 electoral votes.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] All other candidates were on the ballots of fewer than 10 states, 100 electors, and less than 20% of voters nationwide.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The United States presidential election of 2012 broke new records in financing, fundraising, and negative campaigning.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Through grassroots campaign contributions, online donations, and Super PACs, Obama and Romney raised a combined total of more than $2 billion.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Super PACs constituted nearly one-fourth of the total financing, with most coming from pro-Romney PACs.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama raised $690 million through online channels, beating his record of $500 million in 2008.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Most of the advertising in the 2012 presidential campaign was decidedly negative—80% of Obama's ads and 84% of Romney's ads were negative.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The tax-exempt non-profit Americans for Prosperity, a so-called "outside group", that is, a political advocacy group that is not a political action committee or super-PAC, ran a television advertising campaign opposing Obama described by *The Washington Post* as "early and relentless".
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Commission on Presidential Debates held four debates during the last weeks of the campaign: three presidential and one vice-presidential.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The major issues debated were the economy and jobs, the federal budget deficit, taxation and spending, the future of Social Security, Medicare, and Medicaid, healthcare reform, education, social issues, immigration, and foreign policy.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] An independent presidential debate featuring minor party candidates took place on Tuesday, October 23 at the Hilton Hotel in Chicago, Illinois.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The debate was moderated by Larry King and organized by the Free & Equal Elections Foundation.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The participants were Gary Johnson (Libertarian), Jill Stein (Green), Virgil Goode (Constitution), and Rocky Anderson (Justice).
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A second debate between Stein and Johnson took place on Sunday, November 4, and was moderated by Ralph Nader.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Elections analysts and political pundits issue probabilistic forecasts of the composition of the Electoral College.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These forecasts use a variety of factors to estimate the likelihood of each candidate winning the Electoral College electors for that state.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Below is a list of states considered by one or more forecast to be competitive; states that are deemed to be "safe" or "solid" by forecasters *RealClearPolitics*, *Sabato's Crystal Ball*, and *FiveThirtyEight*.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On the day of the election, spread betting firm Spreadex offered an Obama Electoral College Votes spread of 296–300 to Romney's 239–243.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In fact Obama's victory over Romney was greater, winning 332 electoral votes to Romney's 206.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama received 51 percent of the national popular vote to Romney's 47 percent and carried eight of the nine states considered to be electoral battlegrounds.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Altogether, Obama won in 26 states plus the District of Columbia, while Romney carried 24 states.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Of the 3,154 counties/districts/independent cities making returns, Romney won the most popular votes in 2,447 (77.58%) while Obama carried 707 (22.42%).
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The results of the electoral vote were certified by Congress on January 4, 2013.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Popular vote totals are from the Federal Election Commission report.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The table below displays the official vote tallies by each state's Electoral College voting method.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The source for the results of all states, except those that amended their official results, is the official Federal Election Commission report.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The column labeled "Margin" shows Obama's margin of victory over Romney (the margin is negative for every state that Romney won).
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Maine and Nebraska each allow for their election results votes to be split between candidates.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The winner within each congressional district gets one electoral vote for the district.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The winner of the statewide vote gets two additional electoral votes.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the 2012 election, all four of Maine's electoral votes were won by Obama and all five of Nebraska's electoral votes were won by Romney.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After the networks called Ohio for Obama at around 11:15 pm EST on Election Day, Romney was ready to concede the race, but hesitated when Karl Rove strenuously objected on Fox News to the network's decision to make that call.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ohio was arguably the most critical state for Romney, as no Republican has ever won the presidency without carrying it, as of 2026.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Romney campaign had already set up a transition website, and had scheduled and purchased a fireworks display to celebrate in case he won the election.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On November 30, 2012, it was revealed that shortly before the election, internal polling done by the Romney campaign had shown Romney ahead in Colorado and New Hampshire, tied in Iowa, and within a few points of Obama in Wisconsin, Pennsylvania, Minnesota, and Ohio.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In addition, the Romney campaign had assumed that they would win Florida, North Carolina and Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The polls had made Romney and his campaign team so confident of their victory that Romney did not write a concession speech until Obama's victory was announced.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Foreign leaders reacted with both positive and mixed messages.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Most world leaders congratulated and praised Obama on his re-election victory.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, Venezuela and some other states had tempered reactions.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Pakistan commented that Romney's defeat had made Pakistan-United States relations safer.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Stock markets fell noticeably after Obama's re-election, with the Dow Jones Industrial Average, NASDAQ, and the S&P 500 each declining over two percent the day after the election.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] All 50 states had a petition on the White House website We The People calling for their state to secede from the union.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These petitions were created by individual people, with some gaining thousands of signatures.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The United States has a population of 50 million Hispanic and Latino Americans, 27 million of whom are citizens eligible to vote (13% of total eligible voters).
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Exit polls were conducted by Edison Research of Somerville, New Jersey, for the National Election Pool, a consortium which at the time consisted of ABC News, Associated Press, CBS News, CNN, Fox News, and NBC News.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Combined with the re-election victories of his two immediate predecessors, Bill Clinton in 1996 and George W.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bush in 2004, Obama's re-election victory in 2012 marked only the second time in American history that three consecutive incumbent presidents were each won re-elections to their second terms.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was also the first election since 1928 in which neither major-party ticket featured a presidential or vice presidential candidate with any military experience.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The election was arguably decided by three counties: Miami-Dade County (Florida); Cuyahoga County (Ohio) and Philadelphia (Pennsylvania).
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] If these three counties had cast zero votes, Obama would have lost all three states and the election.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This election marked the first time since Franklin D.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Roosevelt's last two re-elections in 1940 and 1944 that the Democratic nominee won a majority of the popular vote (as opposed to a plurality) in two consecutive elections.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama also became the first president of either party to secure a majority of the popular vote in two consecutive elections since Ronald Reagan in 1980 and 1984.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama is the third Democratic president to secure at least 51% of the vote twice, after Andrew Jackson and Franklin D.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Romney won the popular vote in 226 congressional districts making this the first time since 1960 that the winner of the election did not win the popular vote in a majority of the congressional districts.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This is the last time that the Democratic nominee won a majority of states in a presidential election.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Romney lost his home state of Massachusetts, becoming the first major party presidential candidate to lose his home state since Democrat Al Gore lost his home state of Tennessee to Republican George W.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Romney lost his home state by more than 23%, the worst losing margin for a major party candidate since John Frémont in 1856.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Even worse than Frémont, Romney failed to win a single county in his home state, something last seen by Theodore Roosevelt in 1912.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In addition, since Obama carried Ryan's home state of Wisconsin, the Romney–Ryan ticket was the first major party ticket since 1972 to have both of its nominees lose their home states.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Romney won the popular vote in every county of three states: Utah, Oklahoma, and West Virginia; Obama did so in four states: Vermont, Massachusetts, Rhode Island, and Hawaii.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Romney's loss prompted the Republican National Committee to try to appeal to the American Latino population by concentrating on different approaches to immigration.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] These were short-lived due to activity and anger from the Republican base and may have contributed to the selection of Donald Trump as their party's presidential nominee four years later.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Gary Johnson's popular vote total set a Libertarian Party record, and his popular vote percentage was the second-best showing for a Libertarian in a presidential election, trailing only Ed Clark's in 1980.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Johnson would go on to beat this record in the 2016 presidential election, winning the most votes for the Libertarian ticket in history.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] At the time, Green Party candidate Jill Stein's popular vote total made her the most successful female presidential candidate in a general election in United States history.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was later surpassed by Hillary Clinton in 2016.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama is the fifth Democrat to have won re-election to a consecutive term, along with Andrew Jackson, Woodrow Wilson, Franklin D.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This presidential election was the most recent in which no state split its electoral votes, and the most recent in which a candidate received over 60% of the Electoral College vote.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This is the most recent election in which two major party nominees would go on to become president (namely, Obama and Biden).
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama's vote total was the fourth most votes received (behind Obama's 2008 victory and both major candidates in 2020) prior to 2024 and the most ever for a re-elected incumbent president.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The election marked the first time since 1988 in which no state was won by a candidate with a plurality of the state's popular vote.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Furthermore, it is the only post-World War II presidential election in which no states were won by margins smaller than 30,000 votes.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama's narrowest victories were in New Hampshire by 39,643 votes, followed by Florida by 74,309 votes.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Every other presidential election in modern history has seen states narrowly won by several thousand votes.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] As of 2026, this is also the most recent election in which both all of Maine and Nebraska's electoral votes were won by one candidate.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] So far, this is the only presidential election in history where both the Republican and Democratic vice presidential candidates are practicing Roman Catholics.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It is also the only presidential election where there are no white Protestants on a major party ticket.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] As of 2026, Obama is the most recent incumbent president to win a second consecutive term, and this is also the most recent election where any major party won consecutive elections.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama was the first Democrat since Franklin D.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Roosevelt to win a majority of the popular vote more than once.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] While Obama was the first president since Dwight D.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Eisenhower in 1952 and 1956 to receive more than 51% of the popular vote twice, he was also the first president since Franklin D.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Roosevelt in 1936, 1940, and 1944 to win consecutive presidential elections with declining percentages of the popular vote.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama was the most recent of just four presidents in United States history to win re-election with a lower percentage of the electoral vote than in their prior elections, the other three were James Madison in 1812, Woodrow Wilson in 1916 and Franklin D.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Additionally, Obama was the fifth of only five presidents to win re-election with a smaller percentage of the popular vote than in prior elections, the other four are James Madison in 1812, Andrew Jackson in 1832, Grover Cleveland in 1892, and Franklin D.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] All four major candidates for president and vice president went on to hold significant public office after this election.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama and Biden served their second terms as president and vice president, respectively.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Biden initially retired from politics after leaving office, but later was elected president in 2020, defeating Trump, and served one term.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Romney moved to Utah in 2014 and was elected to the Senate there in 2018, succeeding Orrin Hatch, and served one term.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Ryan served three more terms in the House and eventually served as Speaker from 2015 until his retirement from politics in 2019.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The **2013 Virginia gubernatorial election** was held on November 5, 2013, to elect the next governor of Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election was held concurrently with other elections for Virginia's statewide offices, the House of Delegates, and other United States' offices.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Republican governor Bob McDonnell was ineligible to run for re-election as the Constitution of Virginia prohibits its governors from serving consecutive terms.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] This was the 5th consecutive election in which the Republican nominee was an Attorney General of Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Three candidates appeared on the ballot for governor: Republican Ken Cuccinelli, the Attorney General of Virginia; Democrat Terry McAuliffe, a businessman and the former chairman of the Democratic National Committee; and Libertarian Robert Sarvis, a lawyer and businessman.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] McAuliffe won the election and was sworn in as governor on January 11, 2014.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] This was the only Virginia gubernatorial election since 1965 in which no candidate won an outright majority of the vote.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] This was the first gubernatorial election in which the independent city of Bedford became incorporated into Bedford County.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] As of 2026, this remains the only gubernatorial election since 1973 in which the elected governor belonged to the same party as the incumbent U.S. president.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Lieutenant Governor Bill Bolling, elected to the post in 2005, made a deal with McDonnell whereby Bolling would run for re-election as lieutenant governor in 2009, enabling McDonnell to run for governor without a primary, in exchange for McDonnell's support in 2013.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] After the 2009 election, Bolling made no secret of his intention to run for governor in 2013, while Attorney General of Virginia Ken Cuccinelli openly stated that he was considering three options: a run for re-election as attorney general in 2013, running for the U.S.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Senate in 2014, and running for governor in 2013.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Cuccinelli announced to colleagues on December 1, 2011, that he was indeed running for governor.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Bolling responded on the same day that he was disappointed that Cuccinelli decided to challenge him.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Bolling, who was polling poorly against Cuccinelli, withdrew from the race on November 28, 2012.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] He cited the Republican Party's decision to move to a nominating convention rather than hold a primary.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] He ruled out running for another term as lieutenant governor and refused to endorse Cuccinelli.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Bolling considered running as an independent, but decided against it.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Bolling also rejected the possibility of a write-in campaign.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Cuccinelli became the de facto nominee after being the only candidate to file to run by the deadline, and was formally nominated at the state Republican convention on May 18, 2013.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] On April 2, 2013, the Democratic Party of Virginia certified that McAuliffe was the only candidate to file for the June primary and therefore the Democratic nominee.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] On April 21, 2013, the Libertarian Party of Virginia held a special convention and nominated Sarvis as the party's official gubernatorial candidate.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Sarvis' campaign submitted over 17,000 signatures to meet the Virginia State Board of Elections (SBE) requirement of 10,000 valid signatures.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] On June 26, 2013, the SBE confirmed to Sarvis' campaign that he would be listed on the ballot statewide during the elections this November.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] This made Sarvis the fourth minor party gubernatorial nominee to get on the Virginia ballot in 40 years.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Parmele announced his campaign as a write-in candidate in August 2013.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Parmele unsuccessfully ran for the Virginia Beach City Council six times.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] In 2005, he ran as an independent for the 82nd district of the Virginia House of Delegates and lost to incumbent Harry Purkey.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Salahi planned to seek the Republican nomination, but left the party to launch an independent bid.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] However, he failed to submit the necessary signatures to the Virginia State Board of Elections by the June 11, 2013, deadline and did not appear on the ballot as an independent.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] He transitioned his run into a write-in campaign and said he would pursue a congressional seat if he didn't win the governorship.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Salahi also scheduled to have a film document his campaign by Campbell Media Group, but the production company faced legal allegations.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Cuccinelli challenged McAuliffe to a series of 15 debates around the state.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] McAuliffe refused, and called Cuccinelli's challenge "absurd" and a "gimmick".
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Cuccinelli declined to appear at the League of Women Voters/AARP debate, calling it a "left-wing, stacked debate".
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Cuccinelli accepted a debate invitation in Danville for a date in September or October; McAuliffe did not respond.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Sarvis was not invited to the debates or forums; some newspapers, including the *Richmond Times Dispatch*, *The Roanoke Times*, and *The Daily Progress*, called for his inclusion.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Barton Hinkle of the *Richmond Times Dispatch* called the current debate process "stacked" suggesting that debate organizers are activists trying to influence the outcome of the election for their own ideological purposes.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] McAuliffe and his campaign repeatedly declined to give a cost for his spending priorities, stating he would pay for them through unspecified government efficiency improvements, the Medicaid expansion, and federal money from Obamacare.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] McAuliffe said tax increases would not be on the table to pay for policy proposals.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Cuccinelli's 2013 campaign conducted an analysis that found McAuliffe's spending plan would cost at least $14 billion – including $12 billion in new spending – over a four-year term and would translate into a $1,700 tax hike on the average Virginia family.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] McAuliffe's campaign accused Cuccinelli's campaign of "fabricat[ing]" the numbers.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Cuccinelli and McAuliffe met in their first debate on Saturday, July 20, 2013, at the Omni Homestead Resort in Hot Springs, Virginia, for the Virginia Bar Association-sponsored debate.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Both major party candidates attacked their opponent's record, and they debated one another on issues including transportation, federal healthcare, abortion, Virginia Governor Bob McDonnell, same-sex marriage, and other topics.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] PBS' Judy Woodruff moderated the debate.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Libertarian Sarvis was not invited to join the debate, but he attended the event to greet voters.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Cuccinelli and McAuliffe discussed their plans for Virginia's largest industry, agriculture and forest products, on Friday, August 2, 2013, at Wytheville Community College in Wytheville, Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The candidates also discussed topics including transportation and healthcare.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The forum was hosted by the Farm Bureau's Young Farmers Committee.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Cuccinelli and McAuliffe appeared Tuesday, August 6, 2013, at the Norfolk Waterside Marriott in Norfolk, Virginia at an event hosted by Tidewater Community College.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Democrat McAuliffe argued that improving transportation would spur job creation, and he wanted to reform the Standards of Learning and Medicaid.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Republican Cuccinelli focused on tax cuts as well as expanding opportunities for veterans and growing Virginia's ports.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Libertarian Sarvis was not invited to the event, but a spokesman provided a statement about the libertarian candidate.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Cuccinelli and McAuliffe took the stage again on August 9, 2013, at the Hylton Performing Arts Center in Manassas, Virginia, hosted by the chambers of commerce from Loudoun, Prince William, Reston and Fredericksburg.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Both Cuccinelli and McAuliffe answered a series of questions from representatives from each of the chambers that hosted the forum, and both were called out by the event's moderator for dodging specific questions.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The sharpest exchange was between McAuliffe and the forum moderator Derek McGinty, an anchor on WUSA.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] McAuliffe declined to take a position on the proposed Bi-County Parkway, a controversial project that would cut through Manassas National Battlefield Park to connect Prince William and Loudoun counties.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Libertarian Sarvis attended the event but was not included as a candidate, which led some political observers, such as the Franklin Center for Government and Public Integrity's project *watchdog.org*, to say that the number one thing missing from the forum was the invitation to include Sarvis.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Four days after moderating the Battleground Forum, WUSA-TV news anchor Derek McGinty said Sarvis should be part of the conversation.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Consumer Energy Alliance, the National Ocean Industries Association (NOIA), the Thomas Jefferson Institute for Public Policy, and the Virginia Manufacturers Association co-hosted a forum focused on energy with Cuccinelli and McAuliffe on August 29, 2013.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Libertarian Sarvis was not invited to the forum.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The event took place at the George Mason University School of Law campus in Arlington.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Both Cuccinelli and McAuliffe launched broad attacks on one another.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Cuccinelli pointed out McAuliffe's inconsistent stances on coal and offshore drilling (McAuliffe made anti-coal and anti-offshore drilling statements during his 2009 campaign but has attempted to take a more centrist position in 2013).
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Cuccinelli also pointed to the GreenTech scandal enveloping McAuliffe.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] McAuliffe offered few specifics on his own energy policy plans but attacked Cuccinelli for his lawsuit of a Virginia Tech professor and expert on global warming whom he investigated for fraud, and said Cuccinelli's views on social issues would drive away businesses.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Fairfax County Chamber of Commerce and NBC4 hosted a debate between Cuccinelli and McAuliffe on September 25, 2013.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] NBC political journalist Chuck Todd moderated.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The debate was held at the Capital One Bank headquarters in McLean, Virginia, and was aired live on NBC4 and NBC affiliates in Richmond, Charlottesville, Bristol and other Virginia cities.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Throughout the debate, both McAuliffe and Cuccinelli attacked their opponent's records and views.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] McAuliffe focused on Medicaid expansion, failed to answer a question about the price tag of his education plan, and was exposed for not knowing that a state constitutional amendment is required to reverse the state's constitutional ban on same-sex marriage.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Cuccinelli focused on his experience in office, defended his social views, and dodged a question about which loopholes he would close.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] After the debate, the Fairfax County Chamber of Commerce endorsed McAuliffe.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A spokesman said the debate would exclude Sarvis for "no other reason other than our tradition to provide a forum for the two major-party candidates." Sarvis attended the debate and his campaign debuted a television ad, which aired in Northern Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Sarvis ad caused Peter Galuszka of *The Washington Post* to say Sarvis "won" the debate.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Five days after the debate moderator Chuck Todd invited Sarvis onto his show, *The Daily Rundown*, and asked Sarvis questions from the debate.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Virginia Tech and WDBJ sponsored a debate between McAuliffe and Cuccinelli on October 24, 2013.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Prior to the debate, Cuccinelli agreed informally to participate, though his campaign asked questions about the rules, including to raise the threshold for a third-party candidate to participate, before formally agreeing.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Originally, the announced threshold for inclusion in the debate was ten percent in the polls.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Later, it would be announced the threshold for inclusion in the debate was ten percent according to the RealClearPolitics average by the October 10 invitation deadline.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] On October 10, Sarvis was polling at 9% in the RealClearPolitics average, and WDBJ announced that Sarvis would not be included at the debate.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Cuccinelli's funds include $3.97 million from the Republican Governors Association PAC and $500,000 from the Republican Party of Virginia McAuliffe has received 34 contributions of $100,000 or more; Cuccinelli has received six contributions of $100,000 or more.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] 72% of McAuliffe's campaign contributors are from Virginia, but in the first quarter of 2013, 78% of his total funds came from donors from outside Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] 33% of Cuccinelli's funds in the first quarter of 2013 came from donors outside Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Through the first quarter of 2013 ending on March 31, 2013, McAuliffe had raised $6.7 million, and Cuccinelli had raised $4.4 million.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] In the second quarter of 2013, McAuliffe raised $2.2 million, Cuccinelli raised $1.1 million, and Sarvis raised approximately $2,500.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Terry McAuliffe's top five donors are from outside Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Three of Ken Cuccinelli's top five donors are from out-of-state.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Over that period, McAuliffe received 2,010 contributions of more than $100, and 5,476 contributions of $100 or less; while Cuccinelli received 3,193 contributions of more than $100, and 7,075 contributions of $100 or less.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Cuccinelli's biggest donations included several energy companies and private individuals; his largest contribution over the period was $30,000.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] As of August 31, 2013, McAuliffe's campaign has $5,010,223 cash on hand, and Cuccinelli's campaign has $2,234,369 cash on hand.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Tom Steyer's PAC NextGen Climate Action, Michael Bloomberg's PAC Independence USA, the National Education Association and the Planned Parenthood Action Fund have purchased a combined total of over $4.3 million worth of airtime for television ads supporting McAuliffe or opposing Cuccinelli.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Americans for Prosperity, Citizens United, the Virginia Principles Fund PAC, NRA Political Victory Fund, the Ending Spending Fund, and the Fight for Tomorrow PAC have purchased a combined total of just over $2 million worth of airtime for television ads supporting Cuccinelli or opposing McAuliffe.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Purple PAC, a Libertarian-leaning super PAC, spent over $300,000 in television ads designed to boost the Sarvis campaign before election day.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Polls indicated McAuliffe would win comfortably on Election Day.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] However, the race was much closer than expected.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Cuccinelli led for a good portion of the evening.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] However, Fairfax County, a suburb of Washington D.C., is heavily Democratic, and is often one of the last parts of the state to count their votes.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] With around 90% of the vote McAuliffe took the lead for the first time.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] McAuliffe's lead continued to grow as Fairfax County came in.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] With 96% of the vote counted, CNN called the race for McAuliffe.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] EST, Cuccinelli called McAuliffe to concede defeat.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Ralph Northam, also a Democrat, won the race for lieutenant governor, making the governor and the lieutenant governor both Democrats for the first time since 2006.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Despite losing the state, Cuccinelli won seven of 11 congressional districts, while McAuliffe won four, including one held by a Republican.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The result was somewhat surprising because many polls showed McAuliffe with a larger margin of victory over Cuccinelli than he ended up with.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Libertarian candidate was seen as having a large impact on the polls, his presence complicating them and adding "uncertainty to the ballot test".
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The polling for the lieutenant governor and attorney general elections, which did not feature a third-party candidate, was much more accurate.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Although Sarvis also under-performed, this is the best result for a third-party candidate in Virginia since 1965.
[src:governor-of-virginia/2013-virginia-gubernatorial-election] This is the first time since 1885 that a party was voted out of the governor's mansion after just one term.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was born in New Jersey and moved frequently during her childhood before her family settled in Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She earned degrees from the University of Virginia and Purdue University.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] From 2006 to 2014, she was an officer in the Central Intelligence Agency.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] House of Representatives in 2018, unseating incumbent Republican Dave Brat.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She was reelected in 2020 and 2022 before leaving Congress to run for governor.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was elected governor of Virginia in 2025, defeating the Republican nominee, Lieutenant Governor Winsome Earle-Sears.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She is Virginia's first female governor.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] As governor, Spanberger signed a controversial "assault weapons" ban, increased the state's minimum wage, vetoed recreational cannabis retail market and collective bargaining legislation, and supported the 2026 Virginia redistricting referendum.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was born Abigail Anne Davis in Red Bank, New Jersey, on August 7, 1979, her father, Martin Davis, a police officer, and her mother, Eileen Davis, a nurse.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She knew from a young age that she wanted to be a spy, writing her diary in code.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Her family moved often when she was young, living in Maine, the New York City area, and Philadelphia, before settling in Short Pump, Virginia, when she was 13.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Her father had moved from policing to federal law enforcement for the United States Postal Inspection Service.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She graduated from John Randolph Tucker High School and was later a page for U.S. senator Chuck Robb.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger earned a Bachelor of Arts from the University of Virginia in 2001 and a Master of Business Administration from a joint program between the GISMA Business School in Germany and Purdue University's Krannert School of Management.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She initially enrolled at the College of William and Mary before transferring to the University of Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] According to her sister Meredith Schatz, by the time she had completed her undergraduate degree at the University of Virginia, Spanberger was conversationally fluent in Spanish and "five or six more" languages.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] In the early 2000s, Spanberger taught English literature as a substitute teacher at the Islamic Saudi Academy in Northern Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She received a conditional job offer from the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) in December 2002.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] While waiting for a background check to be completed, Spanberger worked as a postal inspector, as her father did, focusing on money laundering and narcotics cases.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] In July 2006, after Spanberger's background check had been completed, she joined the CIA as a case officer, working to find, recruit, and build relationships with foreign nationals who could have had information of value to the U.S. government.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She has publicly said that she gathered intelligence about nuclear proliferation and terrorism.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Her first assignment was to Brussels, according to *The Washington Post*.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] During her career, she held, at some point, five different passports, and met people undercover.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] In 2014, Spanberger left the CIA and entered the private sector.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She was hired by Royall & Company (now a part of EAB) to do consulting work for colleges and universities.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] After the 2016 presidential election, she began working with Emerge America to encourage women to run for state and congressional offices.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] In 2017, Virginia governor Terry McAuliffe appointed her to the Virginia Fair Housing Board.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] In July 2017, Spanberger announced her candidacy for the United States House of Representatives in Virginia's 7th congressional district in the 2018 election against incumbent Republican Dave Brat, a former Tea Party movement member.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She had begun to consider challenging Brat after attending a town hall meeting he hosted in Nottoway County in February 2017 and made the final decision to run in May after the House voted to repeal the Affordable Care Act, texting her husband, "I'm gonna run and I'm gonna f---ing win".
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On June 12, 2018, Spanberger defeated Dan Ward in the Democratic primary election with 73% of the vote, receiving more votes than any other candidate in the Virginia primaries that day.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] In June, after winning the primary, while waiting for a train at the Richmond Staples Mill Road Amtrak station, Spanberger met William C.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Mims, a justice on the Supreme Court of Virginia, who told her he was "impressed with her message".
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] In August, the Congressional Leadership Fund, a super PAC closely aligned with Republican House Speaker Paul Ryan, conducted a smear campaign against Spanberger.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] The campaign, which attempted to tie her to terrorism, was based on an SF-86 application she completed to obtain security clearance, which was released in breach of privacy rules.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] In a visit to the district, former Trump adviser Steve Bannon called the race "an absolute bellwether of the entire country" and said that losing it would mean Republican loss of control of the House.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger won the November 6 general election by about 6,800 votes.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Brat won eight of the district's ten counties, but Spanberger dominated the two largest counties, Henrico and Chesterfield, by a combined margin of over 30,000 votes.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] After winning the election, Virginia Supreme Court Justice Mims wrote her a letter extolling the virtues of public service, leadership, and civility, alongside a copy of former Czech President Václav Havel's essay "Politics, Morality, and Civility".
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger has said the letter and its impact on her leadership were crucial to her development as a politician.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was the first Democrat to win this seat since 1970, when four-term Democrat John Marsh retired and was succeeded by Republican J.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] But until 1993, the 7th stretched from the outer Washington suburbs through the Shenandoah Valley and Charlottesville to the outer Richmond suburbs; the present 7th is geographically and demographically the successor to what was the 3rd district before 1993.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] That district had been in Republican hands since 1981; former House majority leader Eric Cantor represented it from 2001 until Brat ousted him in the 2014 Republican primary.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger and her colleagues Elissa Slotkin and Mikie Sherrill were described as the "mod squad", a moderate alternative to the progressive "squad".
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger and Sherrill shared a Capitol Hill apartment for four years while they served in Congress together.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger faced a close reelection contest against Virginia delegate Nick Freitas, who represented much of the congressional district's northern portion.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She won with 51% of the vote to Freitas's 49%.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Freitas carried eight of the district's ten counties, as Brat had done two years earlier, but Spanberger prevailed by winning the district's shares of Henrico and Chesterfield counties by a combined 43,400 votes, five times her overall margin of 8,400 votes.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She was also boosted by Joe Biden narrowly carrying the district; Biden was the first Democrat to win what is now the 7th Congressional District since 1948.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On November 5, days after winning reelection by a margin of 1.8%, Spanberger criticized the Democratic Party's strategy for the 2020 elections in a phone call with other Democratic caucus members that was subsequently leaked.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Calling the elections "a failure" from a congressional standpoint, she singled out Republican attack ads decrying "socialism" and the movement to "defund the police" as prime reasons the Democratic Party lost seats in swing districts.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger argued that Democrats should watch Republican ads before deciding how to talk about issues and never "use the word 'socialist' or 'socialism' ever again".
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] After the 2020 elections, Spanberger criticized Democratic messaging, arguing that progressive slogans such as "defund the police" and "socialism" had hurt candidates in swing districts.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] CNN political editor Chris Cillizza called her comments "hard truth" for the Democratic Party, adding that for Democrats to succeed in the 2022 and 2024 elections, they should "listen to the likes of Spanberger" rather than push for "the boldest possible progressive legislation".
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] For her first two terms, Spanberger represented a district that stretched from the Richmond suburbs to the fringes of the Shenandoah Valley.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] After the 2020 United States redistricting cycle, Spanberger's district was radically redrawn, and no longer included her home in Henrico County.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She considered not running for reelection in the new district before deciding to do so.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was seen as one of the most vulnerable incumbents of the 2022 election cycle, with pre-election polls projecting a close race with Republican Prince William County supervisor Yesli Vega, a law enforcement officer endorsed by Governor Glenn Youngkin and former president Donald Trump.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger defeated Vega, 52% to 48%, the largest margin at the time in any election Spanberger had run in.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] According to *FiveThirtyEight*'s congressional vote tracker, Spanberger voted with President Trump 8.7% of the time.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] In the 2016 presidential election, Trump won 50% of the vote to Hillary Clinton's 44% in Spanberger's future congressional district.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On September 23, 2019, Spanberger joined six other freshman House Democrats with national security backgrounds in calling for an impeachment inquiry into Trump.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger later announced that she would vote in favor of impeachment, saying, "The President's actions violate his oath of office, endanger our national security, and betray the public trust".
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On June 1, 2020, Spanberger tweeted criticism of Trump's reaction to the George Floyd protests, a series of protests against police brutality that began in Minneapolis on May 26.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On June 2, *The Washington Post* and *The New York Times* quoted Spanberger and several other high-profile former CIA analysts' interpretations of Trump's reaction to the protests as reminiscent of the reaction of totalitarian dictators on the brink of losing control of their dictatorships.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] "As a former CIA officer, I know this playbook, and I know the president's actions are betraying the very foundation of the rule of law he purports to support, the U.S.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger criticized Trump after police used tear gas and rubber bullets on peaceful protestors and a priest during the George Floyd protests to clear a path so that he could have a photo op in front of St.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger opposed Democrats' attempts to amend the Insurrection Act of 1807, saying that amending the rarely used law would not accomplish what Democrats intended.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] According to *PolitiFact*, Spanberger publicly disagreed with some of Biden's immigration policies that have not been subject to congressional votes, but she voted for all 73 bills and resolutions in the House of Representatives that Biden voiced support for.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] In December 2023, she was one of six House Democrats to send Biden a letter criticizing Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's Gaza military strategy.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] In 2020, during a meeting with then-Governor of Virginia Ralph Northam, Northam suggested she should run for governor someday.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger took his advice, and in November 2023 announced that she would not seek reelection to Congress and would instead run for governor of Virginia in the 2025 election.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She secured the uncontested nomination in April 2025.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] In May 2025, while campaigning, Spanberger said she would not sign a bill to fully repeal Virginia's right-to-work law if elected governor.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger is one of the few Virginia gubernatorial candidates to refuse money from Dominion Energy, instead getting donations from the anti-Dominion watchdog Clean Virginia alongside her running mates, who defeated Dominion-backed candidates.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Her priorities on immigration include scrapping Youngkin's immigration order allowing local police to help carry out Trump's ICE raids and deportation policy.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She supports rejoining the Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative, which Youngkin, a Republican, left after Northam had joined it.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was elected in a landslide, securing 58% of the vote.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] The Republican nominee, incumbent lieutenant governor Winsome Earle-Sears, received 42%.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] It was the largest margin of victory for a Democratic gubernatorial candidate in Virginia since Albertis Harrison received just under 64% of the vote in 1961.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] The official vote margin was over 527,000.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] While Democrats won the three statewide races in Virginia in 2025, Spanberger's 15-point margin of victory was the largest.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger outperformed Kamala Harris in the 2024 presidential election in the state by nearly 10 percentage points, while winning 99% of Harris's voters.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On November 5, Spanberger announced her transition team, which included Chris Lu, Daun Hester, and Yohannes Abraham.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Honorary co-chairs of the team included many Democratic Party of Virginia leaders, such as Louise Lucas, Don Scott, Jennifer Wexton, and Rick Boucher.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger's transition informally began on November 6 with a lunch with Governor Youngkin.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On November 12, Spanberger asked the University of Virginia's board of visitors to pause its search for a new president until her transition was complete, drawing criticism from both Youngkin and conservative alumni of the university for supposed politicization of the board process.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger said Youngkin had done the same during his tenure, and promised structural reform to prevent it.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger made her first cabinet appointment on December 2, announcing Marvin Figueroa as Secretary of Health and Human Resources, and continued to make appointments throughout the month.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was sworn in as governor on January 17, 2026.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She was sworn in by former Supreme Court of Virginia Justice William C.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Mims, with her husband Adam holding the Bible and her daughters by her side.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On January 17, 2026, her first day in office, Spanberger signed ten executive orders focusing primarily on affordability, healthcare, housing, education, and preparedness for potential federal policy changes under the Trump administration.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] One of Spanberger's first challenges as governor was managing the January 2026 North American winter storm, responsible for the deaths of four people and hundreds of traffic accidents.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On January 30, Spanberger described the Virginia Leaders in Export Trade (VALET) program, promoting free trade in opposition to Trump's tariffs.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] The Virginia Port Authority is a major hub of international trade.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On January 19, 2026, Spanberger delivered her first address to a joint session of the Virginia General Assembly, emphasizing affordability, bipartisanship, and pragmatic solutions.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She committed to reentering the Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative (RGGI), maintaining Virginia's right-to-work law, collaborating with the federal government where possible, and pushing back against policies harming Virginia jobs or families.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She outlined legislative priorities including lowering healthcare and energy costs, protecting renters, expanding housing production, supporting agriculture amid tariffs, implementing pro-worker measures such as paid family leave and a higher minimum wage, and bipartisan gun safety bills.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Republicans welcomed the calls for unity and right-to-work commitment but proposed alternative tax relief measures and cautioned against increased spending.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger, who campaigned in support of these amendments, said she would campaign for their passage.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] HB736 limits prior authorizations for prescription medication that can lead to costly delays in care.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 30, 2026, the Faith in Housing Act was signed into law.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] It eliminates the rezoning step for faith-based organizations and other tax-exempt nonprofits to develop affordable housing on their properties, allowing religious organizations to give their communities affordable housing with fewer regulatory restrictions.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] SB377 allows utilities to cooperate with high-load energy users to build new substations that exclusively serve them, at the expense of the energy user, to shield other ratepayers from increased costs incurred by their intensive consumption.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger returned the bill to the legislature with amendments on April 13, 2026.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Another amendment removed an exemption for high-load projects approved before July 1, 2026.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] The General Assembly accepted these amendments while rejecting a number of other amendments to the bill.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Shortly after taking office in January 2026, Spanberger reiterated a pledge and long-term policy goal of the state Democratic Party to rejoin the Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative in her first address to the General Assembly.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 22, to commemorate Earth Day, Spanberger signed an executive order committing Virginia to the United States Climate Alliance, a bipartisan coalition of governors committed to sustaining America's fight against climate change with state-led action.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] In May, she signed a slate of legislation aimed at preserving the state's natural resources and treating drinking water for PFAS compounds.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 8, she signed into law HB507, which prohibits the Virginia Department of Environmental Quality from issuing air permits to data centers with backup diesel gen-sets that do not satisfy the Environmental Protection Agency's tier 4 emission standards.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] During her campaign, Spanberger committed to expanding the state's solar and wind energy capacity.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On March 25, Spanberger created the cabinet-level position of Chief Energy Officer via executive order, appointing Southern Environmental Law Center attorney Josephus Allmond to the position.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] The office is tasked with cooperating with the Virginia Secretary of Commerce and Trade, the Virginia Department of Energy, PJM Interconnection, and energy utility providers to address rising energy costs, expand clean energy generation, and develop a statewide energy strategy.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She later signed HB1444, formally codifying the Clean Energy Innovation Bank that had been trialed by the Virginia Department of Energy in 2024, which financed clean energy projects, greenhouse gas emissions reduction projects, and other similar projects.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] The recission order does not force local departments to exit existing agreements with ICE.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Nevertheless, the order has been criticized by Republicans and ICE officials, who have called it a "sanctuary state" policy that has led to an increase in immigrant crime.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] At the same time, she vetoed a law that would have prevented ICE from conducting civil arrests at courthouses, schools, and healthcare facilities.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] The Virginia House of Delegates voted to approve an amendment enshrining abortion access for all Virginia citizens shortly before Spanberger took office.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] The Senate followed suit shortly thereafter.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger signed the bill and sent it to the voters for final approval on February 6, 2026.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 8, Spanberger signed the Right to Contraception Act, enshrining Virginians' right to obtain and use contraceptive drugs or devices and healthcare providers' right to provide them.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 6, 2026, Spanberger signed into law HB1, which would increase the state's hourly minimum wage from $12.77 to $13.75 by January 1, 2027, and $15 by 2028; thereafter the minimum wage will be indexed to increases in the consumer price index and hiked incrementally every year.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Two days later, she signed HB20, which rescinded a statutory exemption from the state minimum wage law for farm laborers and employees, which would go into effect on January 1, 2027.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On May 11, 2026, Spanberger signed a bill establishing a Paid Family and Medical Leave Insurance program administered by the Virginia Employment Commission, set to go into effect in 2028.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] The program will be funded by a trust fund financed by remittances from employers deducted from employee payrolls and, for employers of more than ten workers, employer contributions.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] The law extends benefits to over 1.2 million uncovered workers.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 22, she signed the Equal Pay Act, which prohibits employers from querying prospective workers about their pay history and using that data in considering whether to hire them or in determining their salary unless they voluntarily provide their pay history.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She also signed a bill that expands legal protections against wage theft.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On June 26, 2026, Spanberger signed legislation hiking benefits for unemployment claims filed after July 5 of that year by 11.2%, from $430 to $478 per week.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On May 14, 2026, Spanberger vetoed SB378 and HB1263, collective bargaining legislation backed by the Virginia Service Employees International Union (SEIU) and various labor groups.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] HB542 was the state legislature's most recent effort to expand the commercial sale of recreational cannabis.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] It would have established a framework for the creation of a cannabis retail market administered and regulated by the Virginia Cannabis Control Authority and partially liberalized certain restrictions on sales quantities.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] The General Assembly rejected these recommendations.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] As a result, Spanberger vetoed the bill on May 19, 2026, despite supporting the creation of a retail cannabis market as long as it had strong labeling and regulation.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She cited the bill's "rushed timeframe", which she said gave the state too little time to design comprehensive strategies for regulating the market or to learn from the successes and errors of other states that liberalized cannabis retailing.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Negotiations continued in the following weeks, and they reached a compromise on June 16.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Semi-automatic shotguns for hunting are not considered assault weapons, and semi-automatic firearms owned before July 1 may be retained.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] The law was subject to litigation immediately after being enacted.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] She signed other restrictions relating to the possession of firearms in hospitals, the presence of polling places, and laws relating to gun owners' responsibility to keep their firearms secure.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Bypassing the commission would require another amendment to the Constitution of Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] The General Assembly can pass amendments through a majority vote by the House of Delegates and the Senate in two consecutive legislative sessions, which would send the amendment to be approved by the voters as a ballot measure.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] A corresponding resolution was adopted by the Assembly in October that allows the Virginia General Assembly to consider constitutional amendments related to redistricting during a special session, which was agreed to by the House on the 29th and by the Senate on the 31st.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Both floors reapproved the amendment after the beginning of 164th General Assembly, and Spanberger signed the legislation that sent it to the voters.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] The amendment was ultimately approved, 51.69% to 48.31%.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] It was struck down by the Supreme Court of Virginia on May 8, a ruling appealed by state Democrats.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Supreme Court rejected the appeal on May 15.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] On February 24, 2026, Spanberger delivered the Democratic response to Trump's 2026 State of the Union Address from the chamber of the House of Burgesses in the reconstructed Capitol in Williamsburg, Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Hodges* is overturned, and the Voting Rights Restoration Amendment, which restores voting rights to formerly incarcerated people who completed felony sentences.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] The 2026 legislative session concluded on March 14 with sine die adjournment without a final biennial budget agreement, due to a dispute over data center tax exemptions.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] In April 2026, Spanberger signed a bill that eliminates tax breaks for organizations related to the Confederate States of America, and a package of legislation relating to maternal healthcare and telemedicine.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Most bills would take effect on July 1, 2026.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Very early in Spanberger's governorship, opinion polls showed that her job approval rating was fairly stable and similar to the average of previous Virginia governors.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] A poll by the Institute for Policy and Opinion Research at Roanoke College in early February showed that 53% of Virginians gave her high marks for her job performance, while 38% disapproved.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] By April, her approval rating had dropped significantly, with a *Washington Post*–Schar School poll finding that 47% of voters approved of Spanberger and 46% disapproved.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] This marked the worst net approval rating for a governor in the early months of their term in *Washington Post* polls since the early 1990s.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] Similarly, a State Navigate poll conducted on April 10–13 showed her net approval rating to be breaking even.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] But after the 2026 Virginia redistricting amendment, a *Public Sentiment Institute* poll found that 52% of voters approved of Spanberger and 41% disapproved, as in earlier polls.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p01] In June 2026, *Vox* described Spanberger as polarizing, attempting to placate both businesses and Democrats, while being viewed negatively by Republicans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger positions herself as a moderate Democrat and has called herself a "passionate pragmatist".
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] In the 2019 speaker of the United States House of Representatives election on the opening day of the 116th United States Congress, Spanberger voted for Representative Cheri Bustos, an Illinois Democrat, joining 11 other Democrats who did not back Nancy Pelosi.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, overturning the right to abortion established by *Roe v.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Wade*, saying that "it undermines the right to privacy and a woman's right to choose".
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] She opposes legislation to restrict abortion, saying that the government should not "mandate a pregnancy".
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] During her gubernatorial campaign, Spanberger said she would support a constitutional amendment to restore "the *Roe* standard" and that she supported Virginia's existing laws requiring minors seeking abortions to receive parental consent, and certain limitations on third-trimester abortions.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] In February 2023, Spanberger was one of 12 House Democrats who voted in favor of H.J.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] 7, a Republican-sponsored resolution to terminate the national emergency concerning COVID-19 declared in March 2020.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] During her 2025 campaign for governor of Virginia, a January 6, 2021, photograph of Spanberger wearing an emergency escape hood inside the Capitol was circulated online by critics, who misrepresented it as COVID-19 protective gear and mocked her.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] In 2023, Spanberger voted against overturning the District of Columbia's revision of its criminal code, which reduced the maximum penalties for burglary, carjacking, and robbery.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger opposes defunding the police, and has supported bills that would increase the ability of local police departments to hire and train more officers.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Although she was not a member of Congress when it passed, Spanberger criticized the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act supported by President Donald Trump, arguing that its permanent tax cuts for corporations would increase the national debt.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger called for the passage of the USMCA trade deal negotiated by the Trump administration, Mexico, and Canada.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger opposed Trump's tariffs during her 2025 gubernatorial campaign.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] She has promoted free trade during her tenure as governor.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] In May 2020, Spanberger voted against the HEROES Act, a proposed $3 trillion stimulus package in response to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] She said the bill went "far beyond" pandemic relief and had no chance of passing the Republican-controlled Senate.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] In November 2020, Spanberger led a bipartisan effort to secure the 340B Drug Pricing Program against changes that would lead to significant increases in prescription medication costs.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger supports banning members of Congress from trading stocks.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] She has introduced legislation that would require lawmakers, as well as their spouses and dependent children, to place assets in a blind trust while in office.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] In September 2025, Spanberger wrote an opinion article in *The Washington Post* opposing DOGE for conducting mass layoffs of federal workers in 2025 which particularly affect Virginia, as many federal workers live there.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger focused her 2025 gubernatorial campaign on affordability and jobs.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Through her "Strengthening Virginia Schools Plan", Spanberger announced she would make higher education more affordable and accessible and make it easier for high school students to take college-level courses.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] She supports allowing teachers to deliver instruction and manage curriculum without interference from political bodies or agendas.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger has emphasized strengthening public schools by hiring and fairly compensating teachers, rather than supporting private schools and school choice.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger has called climate change "one of the greatest and most imminent threats to our economy, our national security, and our way of life" and said she will "stand up to attacks against science".
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] During a 2019 Committee on Foreign Affairs meeting, she asked the Trump administration to reverse its isolationist policies, saying, "it's in our national interest to reinforce our stature as a global leader on international environmental and energy issues".
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger called the Green New Deal proposed by Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez a "bold compilation of ideas meant to address global climate change" but criticized it for allegedly including unrelated policy proposals and not identifying specific resolutions to the problems that it identifies.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] "Overall I am not a supporter of the Green New Deal", she said.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] In February 2023, during the Russo–Ukrainian War, Spanberger signed a letter advocating that President Biden give Ukraine F-16 fighter jets.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] In June 2025, Spanberger supported the U.S. strikes on Iranian nuclear sites.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger has called for a new version of the Federal Assault Weapons Ban that expired in 2004.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] She favors requiring background checks on private gun sales and supported a ban on bump stocks.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Before she served in Congress, Spanberger volunteered with Moms Demand Action, a gun-control advocacy group.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger supports the Affordable Care Act (Obamacare).
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] She supports a public option for healthcare via the proposed Medicare-X Choice Act.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] In November 2020, she called reducing the cost of prescription drugs "the top priority of families in my district".
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] In January 2020, Spanberger sponsored the Public Disclosure of Drug Discounts Act, which passed the House unanimously.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] The bill requires pharmacy benefit managers (PBMs), who manage prescription drug benefits for health insurance companies, to publicize the rebates, discounts, and price concessions they negotiate, via a website hosted by the U.S. secretary of health and human services.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger also co-sponsored the Elijah Cummings Lower Drug Costs Now Act, which grants Medicare Part D the power to negotiate prescription prices directly with drug companies.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger objected to President Trump's travel bans from certain predominantly Muslim countries and argued that they would aid jihadist propaganda by allowing a portrayal of the U.S. as an anti-Muslim country.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] She has voiced her support for stronger border security measures but opposes Trump's proposed wall.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger voted for a bill that included funding for border infrastructure, technology at ports of entry, and more customs and border protection officers and agents.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] She said she does not support "sanctuary cities" but also called the term "a campaign slogan a lot of people get caught up in".
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] She added that it "degrades the value of the conversation if we're not actually talking about what the real concern is." Spanberger called for a pathway to legal status for illegal immigrants who abide by the laws, work, and pay taxes.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Immigration and Customs Enforcement to be notified when undocumented immigrants attempt to purchase firearms.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] In 2022, she voted in favor of the Respect for Marriage Act.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] When Spanberger ran for governor in 2025, she was endorsed by the Human Rights Campaign, an LGBTQ advocacy group.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] In April 2006 she married Adam Spanberger, a University of Virginia-trained engineer, and her high school sweetheart.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] She helped run a Girl Scouts troop for her daughters when they were young.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] In 2014, the family moved to Henrico County.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] Before Spanberger became governor, they lived in Glen Allen, Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/abigail-spanberger-p02] During her time in Congress, Spanberger roomed with colleague Mikie Sherrill, who was elected governor of New Jersey on the same day Spanberger was elected governor of Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] African-American history began in the 16th century, when mainly West African and Central African slave traders sold African artisans, farmers, and warriors to European slave traders, who transported them across the Atlantic to the Western Hemisphere.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] They were sold as slaves to European colonists and put to work on plantations, particularly in the southern colonies.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] A few were able to achieve freedom through manumission or escape, and founded independent communities before and during the American Revolution.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] After the United States was founded in 1783, most American Black people continued to be enslaved, primarily in the American South, with four million enslaved people only liberated after the Northern victory over the South in the Civil War of 1861 to 1865.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] During Reconstruction, African Americans gained citizenship and adult-males the right to vote; however, due to widespread belief in White supremacy, they were treated as second-class citizens and soon effectively disenfranchised in the South.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] These circumstances changed due to participation in the military conflicts of the United States, substantial migration out of the South, the elimination of legal racial segregation, and the civil rights movement which sought political and social freedom.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] However, racism against African Americans and racial socioeconomic disparity remain a problem into the 21st century.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In the 20th and 21st centuries, immigration has played an increasingly significant role in the African-American community.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Black population were immigrants, and 20% were either immigrants or the children of immigrants.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] While some Black immigrants or their children may also come to identify as African American, the majority of first-generation immigrants do not, preferring to identify with their nation of origin.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Most African Americans are of West African and coastal Central African ancestry, with varying amounts of Western European and Native American ancestry (see §Genetics).
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] African-American culture has had a significant influence on worldwide culture, making numerous contributions to the English language, literature, politics, cuisine, sports, and music.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The African-American contribution to popular music is so profound that most American popular music, including gospel, blues, jazz, rock and roll, R&B, soul, funk, disco, hip-hop, and house has its origins either partially or entirely in the African-American community.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The vast majority of those who were enslaved and transported in the transatlantic slave trade were people from several Central and West African ethnic groups.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] They had been captured directly by European slave traders in coastal raids, or captured and sold by West African slave traders or by half-European "merchant princes" to European slave traders, who brought them to the Americas.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The first African slaves in what is now the United States arrived in the early 16th century.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Africans were among Juan Ponce de León's 1513 voyage that landed in what would become Spanish Florida, and enslaved Africans arrived around the same time to Spanish Puerto Rico.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Africans also came via Santo Domingo in the Caribbean to the San Miguel de Gualdape colony (most likely located in the Winyah Bay area of present-day South Carolina), founded by Spanish explorer Lucas Vázquez de Ayllón in 1526.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The ill-fated colony was almost immediately disrupted by a fight over leadership, during which the slaves revolted and fled the colony to seek refuge among local Native Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] De Ayllón and many of the colonists died shortly afterward, due to an epidemic and the colony was abandoned.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The settlers and the slaves who had not escaped returned to the Island of Hispaniola, whence they had come.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The enslaved explorer Esteban arrived in Florida with the Narváez expedition in 1528, a journey that first landed in Santo Domingo and later traveled into Spanish Texas and the Southwest before ending in Mexico.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The marriage between Luisa de Abrego, a free Black domestic servant from Seville, and Miguel Rodríguez, a White Segovian conquistador in 1565 in St.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Augustine (Spanish Florida), is the first known and recorded Christian marriage anywhere in what is now the continental United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The first recorded Africans in English America (including most of the future United States) were "20 and odd negroes" who arrived in Jamestown, Virginia via Cape Comfort in August 1619 as indentured servants.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] As many Virginian settlers began to die from harsh conditions, more and more Africans were brought to work as laborers.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] An indentured servant (who could be White or Black) would work for several years (usually four to seven) without wages.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The status of indentured servants in early Virginia and Maryland was similar to slavery.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Servants could be bought, sold, or leased, and they could be physically beaten for disobedience or attempting to running away.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Unlike slaves, they were freed after their term of service expired or if their freedom was purchased.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Their children did not inherit their status, and on their release from contract they received "a year's provision of corn, double apparel, tools necessary", and a small cash payment called "freedom dues".
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Africans could legally raise crops and cattle to purchase their freedom.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] They raised families, married other Africans and sometimes intermarried with Native Americans or European settlers.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] By the 1640s and 1650s, several African families owned farms around Jamestown, and some became wealthy by colonial standards and purchased indentured servants of their own.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In 1640, the Virginia General Court recorded the earliest documentation of lifetime slavery when they sentenced John Punch, a Negro, to lifetime servitude under his master Hugh Gwyn, for running away.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In Spanish Florida, some Spanish married or had unions with Pensacola, Creek or African women, both enslaved and free, and their descendants created a mixed-race population of mestizos and mulattos.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The Spanish encouraged slaves from the colony of Georgia to come to Florida as a refuge, promising freedom in exchange for conversion to Catholicism.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] King Charles II issued a royal proclamation freeing all slaves who fled to Spanish Florida and accepted conversion and baptism.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Augustine, but escaped slaves also reached Pensacola.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Augustine had mustered an all-Black militia unit defending Spanish Florida as early as 1683.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] One of the Dutch African arrivals, Anthony Johnson, would later own one of the first Black "slaves", John Casor, resulting from the court ruling of a civil case.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The popular conception of a race-based slave system did not fully develop until the 18th century.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The Dutch West India Company introduced slavery in 1625 with the importation of eleven Black slaves into New Amsterdam (present-day New York City).
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] All the colony's slaves, however, were freed upon its surrender to the English.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Massachusetts was the first English colony to legally recognize slavery in 1641.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In 1662, Virginia passed a law that children of enslaved women would take the status of the mother, rather than that of the father, as was the case under common law.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] This legal principle was called *partus sequitur ventrum*.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] By an act of 1699, Virginia ordered the deportation of all free Blacks, effectively defining all people of African descent who remained in the colony as slaves.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In 1670, the colonial assembly passed a law prohibiting free and baptized Blacks (and Native Americans) from purchasing Christians (in this act meaning White Europeans) but allowing them to buy people "of their owne nation".
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In Spanish Louisiana, although there was no movement toward abolition of the African slave trade, Spanish rule introduced a new law called *coartación*, which allowed slaves to buy their freedom, and that of others.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Although some did not have the money to do so, government measures on slavery enabled the existence of many free Blacks.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] This caused problems to the Spaniards with the French creoles (French who had settled in New France) who had also populated Spanish Louisiana.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The French creoles cited that measure as one of the system's worst elements.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] First established in South Carolina in 1704, groups of armed White men—slave patrols—were formed to monitor enslaved Black people.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Their function was to police slaves, especially fugitives.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Slave owners feared that slaves might organize revolts or slave rebellions, so state militias were formed to provide a military command structure and discipline within the slave patrols.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] These patrols were used to detect, encounter, and crush any organized slave meetings which might lead to revolts or rebellions.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The earliest African American congregations and churches were organized before 1800 in both northern and southern cities following the Great Awakening.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] By 1775, Africans made up 20% of the population in the American colonies, which made them the second-largest ethnic group after English Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] During the 1770s, Africans, both enslaved and free, helped rebellious American colonists secure their independence by defeating the British in the American Revolutionary War.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Blacks played a role in both sides in the American Revolution.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Activists in the Patriot cause included James Armistead, Prince Whipple, and Oliver Cromwell.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Around 15,000 Black Loyalists left with the British after the war, most of them ending up as free Black people in England or its colonies, such as the Black Nova Scotians and the Sierra Leone Creole people.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In the Spanish Louisiana, Governor Bernardo de Gálvez organized Spanish free Black men into two militia companies to defend New Orleans during the American Revolution.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] They fought in the 1779 battle in which Spain captured Baton Rouge from the British.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Gálvez also commanded them in campaigns against the British outposts in Mobile, Alabama, and Pensacola, Florida.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] He recruited slaves for the militia by pledging to free anyone who was seriously wounded and promised to secure a low price for *coartación* (buy their freedom and that of others) for those who received lesser wounds.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] During the 1790s, Governor Francisco Luis Héctor, baron of Carondelet reinforced local fortifications and recruit even more free Black men for the militia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Carondelet doubled the number of free Black men who served, creating two more militia companies—one made up of Black members and the other of pardo (mixed race).
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Serving in the militia brought free Black men one step closer to equality with Whites, allowing them, for example, the right to carry arms and boosting their earning power.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] However, actually these privileges distanced free Black men from enslaved Blacks and encouraged them to identify with Whites.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Slavery had been tacitly enshrined in the US Constitution through provisions such as Article I, Section 2, Clause 3, commonly known as the 3/5 compromise.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Due to the restrictions of Section 9, Clause 1, Congress was unable to pass an Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves until 1807.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Fugitive slave laws (derived from the Fugitive Slave Clause of the Constitution—Article IV, Section 2, Clause 3) were passed by Congress in both 1793 and 1850, guaranteeing the right of a slaveholder to recover an escaped slave anywhere within the US.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Slave owners, who viewed enslaved people as property, ensured that it became a federal crime to aid or assist those who had fled slavery or to interfere with their capture.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] By that time, slavery, which almost exclusively targeted Black people, had become the most critical and contentious political issue in the Antebellum United States, repeatedly sparking crises and conflicts.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Among these were the Missouri Compromise, the Compromise of 1850, the infamous Dred Scott decision, and John Brown's raid on Harpers Ferry.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Prior to the Civil War, eight serving presidents had owned slaves, a practice that was legally protected under the US Constitution.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] By 1860, the number of enslaved Black people in the US had grown to between 3.5 and 4.4 million, largely as a result of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In addition, 488,000–500,000 Black people lived free around the country, with legislated limits imposed upon them in addition to "unconquerable prejudice" from Whites according to Henry Clay.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In response to these conditions, some free Black people chose to leave the US and emigrate to Liberia in West Africa.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Liberia had been established in 1821 as a settlement by the American Colonization Society (ACS), with many abolitionist members of the ACS believing Black Americans would have greater opportunities for freedom and equality in Africa than they would in the US.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Slaves not only represented a significant financial investment for their owners, but they also played a crucial role in producing the country's most valuable product and export: cotton.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Enslaved people were instrumental in the construction of several prominent structures such as, the United States Capitol, the White House and other Washington, D.C.–based buildings.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Similar building projects existed in the slave states.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] By 1815, the domestic slave trade had become a significant and major economic activity in the United States, continuing to flourish until the 1860s.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Historians estimate that nearly one million individuals were subjected to this forced migration, which was often referred to as a new "Middle Passage".
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The historian Ira Berlin described this internal forced migration of enslaved people as the "central event" in the life of a slave during the period between the American Revolution and the Civil War.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Berlin emphasized that whether enslaved individuals were directly uprooted or lived in constant fear that they or their families would be involuntarily relocated, "the massive deportation traumatized Black people" throughout the US.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] As a result of this large-scale forced movement, countless individuals lost their connection to families and clans, and many ethnic Africans lost their knowledge of varying tribal origins in Africa.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Emigration of free Blacks to their continent of origin had been proposed since the Revolutionary war.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] After Haiti became independent, it tried to recruit African Americans to migrate there after it re-established trade relations with the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The Haitian Union was a group formed to promote relations between the countries.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] After riots against Blacks in Cincinnati, its Black community sponsored founding of the Wilberforce Colony, an initially successful settlement of African American immigrants to Canada.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The colony was one of the first such independent political entities.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] It lasted for a number of decades and provided a destination for about 200 Black families emigrating from a number of locations in the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In 1863, during the American Civil War, President Abraham Lincoln signed the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The proclamation declared that all slaves in Confederate-held territory were free.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Advancing Union troops enforced the proclamation, with Texas being the last state to be emancipated, in 1865.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Slavery in a few border states continued until the ratification of the Thirteenth Amendment in December 1865.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] While the Naturalization Act of 1790 limited US citizenship to Whites only, the 14th Amendment (1868) gave Black people citizenship, and the 15th Amendment (1870) gave Black men the right to vote.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] African Americans quickly set up congregations for themselves, as well as schools and community/civic associations, to have space away from White control or oversight.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] While the post-war Reconstruction era was initially a time of progress for African Americans, that period ended in 1876.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] By the late 1890s, Southern states enacted Jim Crow laws to enforce racial segregation and disenfranchisement.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Segregation was now imposed with Jim Crow laws, using signs used to show Blacks where they could legally walk, talk, drink, rest, or eat.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] For those places that were racially mixed, non-Whites had to wait until all White customers were dealt with.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Most African Americans obeyed the Jim Crow laws, to avoid racially motivated violence.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] To maintain self-esteem and dignity, African Americans such as Anthony Overton and Mary McLeod Bethune continued to build their own schools, churches, banks, social clubs, and other businesses.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In the last decade of the 19th century, racially discriminatory laws and racial violence aimed at African Americans began to mushroom in the United States, a period often referred to as the "nadir of American race relations".
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] These discriminatory acts included racial segregation—upheld by the United States Supreme Court decision in *Plessy v.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The desperate conditions of African Americans in the South sparked the Great Migration during the first half of the 20th century which led to a growing African American community in Northern and Western United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The rapid influx of Blacks disturbed the racial balance within Northern and Western cities, exacerbating hostility between both Blacks and Whites in the two regions.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The Red Summer of 1919 was marked by hundreds of deaths and higher casualties across the US as a result of race riots that occurred in more than three dozen cities, such as the Chicago race riot of 1919 and the Omaha race riot of 1919.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Overall, Blacks in Northern and Western cities experienced systemic discrimination in a plethora of aspects of life.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Within employment, economic opportunities for Blacks were routed to the lowest-status and restrictive in potential mobility.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] While many Whites defended their space with violence, intimidation, or legal tactics toward African Americans, many other Whites migrated to more racially homogeneous suburban or exurban regions, a process known as White flight.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Despite discrimination, drawing cards for leaving the hopelessness in the South were the growth of African American institutions and communities in Northern cities.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Institutions included Black oriented organizations (e.g., Urban League, NAACP), churches, businesses, and newspapers, as well as successes in the development in African American intellectual culture, music, and popular culture (e.g., Harlem Renaissance, Chicago Black Renaissance).
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The Cotton Club in Harlem was a Whites-only establishment, with Blacks (such as Duke Ellington) allowed to perform, but to a White audience.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Black Americans also found a new ground for political power in Northern cities, without the enforced disabilities of Jim Crow.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] By the 1950s, the civil rights movement was gaining momentum.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] A 1955 lynching that sparked public outrage about injustice was that of Emmett Till, a 14-year-old boy from Chicago.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Spending the summer with relatives in Money, Mississippi, Till was killed for allegedly having wolf-whistled at a White woman.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Till had been badly beaten, one of his eyes was gouged out, and he was shot in the head.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The visceral response to his mother's decision to have an open-casket funeral mobilized the Black community throughout the US.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Vann Newkirk wrote "the trial of his killers became a pageant illuminating the tyranny of White supremacy".
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The state of Mississippi tried two defendants, but they were speedily acquitted by an all-White jury.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom and the conditions which brought it into being are credited with putting pressure on presidents John F.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] By 1966, the emergence of the Black Power movement, which lasted from 1966 to 1975, expanded upon the aims of the civil rights movement to include economic and political self-sufficiency, and freedom from White authority.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] During the post-war period, many African Americans continued to be economically disadvantaged relative to other Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Average Black income stood at 54 percent of that of White workers in 1947, and 55 percent in 1962.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In 1965, 43 percent of all Black families fell into the poverty bracket, earning under $3,000 (equivalent to $30,649 in 2025) a year.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] The 1960s saw improvements in the social and economic conditions of many Black Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] From 1965 to 1969, Black family income rose from 54 to 60 percent of White family income.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In 1968, 23 percent of Black families earned under $3,000 (equivalent to $27,775 in 2025) a year, compared with 41 percent in 1960.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In 1965, 19 percent of Black Americans had incomes equal to the national median, a proportion that rose to 27 percent by 1967.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In 1960, the median level of education for Blacks had been 10.8 years, and by the late 1960s, the figure rose to 12.2 years, half a year behind the median for Whites.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Politically and economically, African Americans have made substantial strides during the post–civil rights era.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In 1967, Thurgood Marshall became the first African American Supreme Court Justice.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In 1968, Shirley Chisholm became the first Black woman elected to the US Congress.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In 1989, Douglas Wilder became the first African American elected governor in US history.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Clarence Thomas succeeded Marshall to become the second African American Supreme Court Justice in 1991.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In 1992, Carol Moseley-Braun of Illinois became the first African American woman elected to the US Senate.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] There were 8,936 Black officeholders in the United States in 2000, showing a net increase of 7,467 since 1970.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In 2005, the number of Africans immigrating to the United States, in a single year, surpassed the peak number who were involuntarily brought to the United States during the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] On November 4, 2008, Democratic Senator Barack Obama—the son of a White American mother and a Kenyan father—defeated Republican Senator John McCain to become the first African American to be elected president.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] At least 95 percent of African American voters voted for Obama.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] He also received overwhelming support from young and educated Whites, a majority of Asians, and Hispanics, picking up a number of new states in the Democratic electoral column.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Obama lost the overall White vote, although he won a larger proportion of White votes than any previous non-incumbent Democratic presidential candidate since Jimmy Carter.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] Obama was reelected for a second and final term, by a similar margin on November 6, 2012.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In 2021, Kamala Harris, the daughter of a Jamaican father and Indian mother, became the first woman, the first African American, and the first Asian American to serve as Vice President of the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p01] In June 2021, Juneteenth, a day which commemorates the end of slavery in the US, became a federal holiday.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 1790, when the first US census was taken, Africans (including slaves and free people) numbered about 760,000—about 19.3% of the population.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 1860, at the start of the Civil War, the African American population had increased to 4.4 million, but the percentage rate dropped to 14% of the overall population of the country.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The vast majority were slaves, with only 488,000 counted as "freemen".
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] By 1900, the Black population had doubled and reached 8.8 million.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 1910, about 90% of African Americans lived in the South.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Large numbers began migrating north looking for better job opportunities and living conditions, and to escape Jim Crow laws and racial violence.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The Great Migration, as it was called, spanned the 1890s to the 1970s.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] From 1916 through the 1960s, more than six million Black people moved north.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] But in the 1970s and 1980s, that trend reversed, with more African Americans moving south to the Sun Belt than leaving it.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] By 1990, the African American population reached about 30 million and represented 12% of the US population, roughly the same proportion as in 1900.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] At the time of the 2000 US census, 54.8% of African Americans lived in the South.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In that year, 17.6% of African Americans lived in the Northeast and 18.7% in the Midwest, while only 8.9% lived in the Western states.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The west does have a sizable Black population in certain areas, however.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] California, the nation's most populous state, has the fifth-largest African American population, only behind New York, Texas, Georgia, and Florida.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] According to the 2000 census, approximately 2.05% of African Americans identified as Hispanic or Latino in origin, many of whom may be of Brazilian, Puerto Rican, Dominican, Cuban, Haitian, or other Latin American descent.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The only self-reported *ancestral* groups larger than African Americans are the Irish and Germans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] According to the 2010 census, nearly 3% of people who self-identified as Black had recent ancestors who immigrated from another country.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Self-reported non-Hispanic Black immigrants from the Caribbean, mostly from Jamaica and Haiti, represented 0.9% of the US population, at 2.6 million.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Self-reported Black immigrants from sub-Saharan Africa also represented 0.9%, at about 2.8 million.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Additionally, self-identified Black Hispanics represented 0.4% of the United States population, at about 1.2 million people, largely found within the Puerto Rican and Dominican communities.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Self-reported Black immigrants hailing from other countries in the Americas, such as Brazil and Canada, as well as several European countries, represented less than 0.1% of the population.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Mixed-race Hispanic and non-Hispanic Americans who identified as being part Black, represented 0.9% of the population.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Of the 12.6% of United States residents who identified as Black, around 10.3% were "native Black American" or ethnic African Americans, who are direct descendants of West/Central Africans brought to the US as slaves.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] These individuals make up well over 80% of all Blacks in the country.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] When including people of mixed-race origin, about 13.5% of the US population self-identified as Black or "mixed with Black".
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] However, according to the US Census Bureau, evidence from the 2000 census indicates that many African and Caribbean immigrant ethnic groups do not identify as "Black, African Am., or Negro".
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Instead, they wrote in their own respective ethnic groups in the "Some Other Race" write-in entry.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] As a result, the census bureau devised a new, separate "African American" ethnic group category in 2010 for ethnic African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Nigerian Americans and Ethiopian Americans were the most reported sub-Saharan African groups in the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In the 2020 census, the African American population was undercounted at an estimated rate of 3.3%, up from 2.1% in 2010.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Texas has the largest African American population by state with approximately four million.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Followed by Texas is Florida, with 3.8 million, and Georgia, with 3.6 million.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Mississippi is the state with the highest African American share of the population at 39%.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Followed by Mississippi is Louisiana at 34%, and Georgia at 32%.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] After 100 years of African Americans leaving the south in large numbers seeking better opportunities and treatment in the west and north, a movement known as the Great Migration, there is now a reverse trend, called the New Great Migration.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] As with the earlier Great Migration, the New Great Migration is primarily directed toward cities and large urban areas, such as Charlotte, Houston, Dallas, Fort Worth, Huntsville, Raleigh, Tampa, San Antonio, New Orleans, Memphis, Nashville, Jacksonville, and so forth.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] A growing percentage of African Americans from the west and north are migrating to the southern region of the US for economic and cultural reasons.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 2020, New York City, Chicago, and Los Angeles metropolitan areas had the highest decline in African Americans, while Atlanta, Dallas, and Houston had the highest increase respectively.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Despite recent declines, as of 2020, the New York City metropolitan area still has the largest African American metropolitan population in the United States and the only to have over three million African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Among cities of 100,000 or more, South Fulton, Georgia had the highest percentage of Black residents of any large US city in 2020, with 93%.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Claiborne County, Mississippi is the Blackest county in the U.S. at 87% Black in 2020.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Cook County, Illinois has the largest Black population in the U.S. with 1,185,601 Black residents in 2020.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The nation's most affluent community with an African American majority resides in View Park–Windsor Hills, California, with an annual median household income of $159,618 and median home price of about $1.5 million in 2025.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Additionally, there is a significant affluent Black presence in the southern Chicago suburbs of Cook County, Illinois.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 2006, Queens County, New York was the only county with a population of 65,000 or more where African Americans had a higher median household income than White Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Seatack, Virginia is currently the oldest African American community in the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] It survives today with a vibrant and active civic community.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] During slavery, anti-literacy laws were enacted in the US that prohibited education for Black people.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Slave owners saw literacy as a threat to the institution of slavery.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] When slavery was finally abolished in 1865, public educational systems were expanding across the country.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] By 1870, around seventy-four institutions in the south provided a form of advanced education for African American students.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] By 1900, over a hundred programs at these schools provided training for Black professionals, including teachers.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Many of the students at Fisk University, including the young W.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Du Bois, taught school during the summers to support their studies.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African Americans were very concerned to provide quality education for their children, but White supremacy limited their ability to participate in educational policymaking on the political level.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] State governments soon moved to undermine their citizenship by restricting their right to vote.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] By the late 1870s, Blacks were disenfranchised and segregated across the American South.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] White politicians in Mississippi and other states withheld financial resources and supplies from Black schools.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Nevertheless, the presence of Black teachers, and their engagement with their communities both inside and outside the classroom, ensured that Black students had access to education despite these external constraints.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] During World War II, demands for unity and racial tolerance on the home front provided an opening for the first Black history curriculum in the country.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] For example, during the early 1940s, Madeline Morgan, a Black teacher in the Chicago public schools, created a curriculum for students in grades one through eight highlighting the contributions of Black people to the history of the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] At the close of the war, Chicago's Board of Education downgraded the curriculum's status from mandatory to optional.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Predominantly Black schools for kindergarten through twelfth grade students were common throughout the US before the 1970s.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] By 1972, however, desegregation efforts meant that only 25% of Black students were in schools with more than 90% non-White students.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] However, since then, a trend towards re-segregation affected communities across the country: by 2011, 2.9 million African American students were in such overwhelmingly minority schools, including 53% of Black students in school districts that were formerly under desegregation orders.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] As late as 1947, about one third of African Americans over 65 were considered to lack the literacy to read and write their own names.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] By 1969, illiteracy as it had been traditionally defined, had been largely eradicated among younger African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Between 1995 and 2009, freshmen college enrollment for African Americans increased by 73 percent and only 15 percent for Whites.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Black women are enrolled in college more than any other race and gender group, leading all with 9.7% enrolled according to the 2011 US census.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The average high school graduation rate of Blacks in the United States has steadily increased to 71% in 2013.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Separating this statistic into component parts shows it varies greatly depending upon the state and the school district examined.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] 38% of Black males graduated in the state of New York but in Maine 97% graduated and exceeded the White male graduation rate by 11 percentage points.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In much of the southeastern United States and some parts of the southwestern United States the graduation rate of White males was in fact below 70% such as in Florida where 62% of White males graduated from high school.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Examining specific school districts paints an even more complex picture.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In the Detroit school district, the graduation rate of Black males was 20% but 7% for White males.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In the New York City school district 28% of Black males graduate from high school compared to 57% of White males.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In Newark County 76% of Black males graduated compared to 67% for White males.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Further academic improvement has occurred in 2015.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Roughly 23% of all Blacks have bachelor's degrees.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 1988, 21% of Whites had obtained a bachelor's degree versus 11% of Blacks.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 2015, 23% of Blacks had obtained a bachelor's degree versus 36% of Whites.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Foreign born Blacks, 9% of the Black population, made even greater strides.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] They exceed native born Blacks by 10 percentage points.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] College Board, which runs the official college-level advanced placement (AP) programs in American high schools, have has received criticism in recent years that its curricula have focused too much on Euro-centric history.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 2020, College Board reshaped some curricula among history-based courses to further reflect the African diaspora.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 2021, College Board announced it would be piloting an AP African American Studies course between 2022 and 2024.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The course officially launched in August 2024.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In June 2023, the Supreme Court ended race-based affirmative action at American colleges and universities.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In response, many of the nation's most prominent historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs) have reported a significant surge in applications and enrollment.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Slightly more than 250,000 African American students in the high school graduating class of 2025 took the Scholastic Aptitude Test (SAT) making up 13% of test takers.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African American students had an average score of 904 which is lower than the national average of 1,209.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Asian American students had the highest average with 1,229.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] According to a 2025 study, African Americans have the highest average student debt.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African Americans with bachelor's degrees owe an average of $52,726 in student loans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Nearly 70% of African Americans took out a loan to fund their undergraduate education.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African American women, in particular, carry the highest average student debt in the nation.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs), which were founded when segregated institutions of higher learning did not admit African Americans, continue to thrive and educate students of all races today.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] There are 107 HBCUs representing three percent of the nation's colleges and universities with the majority established in the Southeast.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] HBCUs have been largely responsible for establishing and expanding the African American middle-class by providing more career opportunities for African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The economic disparity between the races in the US has marginally improved since the end of slavery.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 1863, two years prior to emancipation, Black people owned 0.5 percent of the national wealth, while in 2019 it is just over 1.5 percent.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Racial disparity in poverty rates has narrowed since the civil rights era, with the poverty rate among African Americans decreasing from 24.7% in 2004 to 18.8% in 2020, compared to 10.5% for all Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Poverty is associated with higher rates of marital stress and dissolution, physical and mental health problems, disability, cognitive deficits, low educational attainment, and crime.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African Americans have a long and diverse history of business ownership.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Although the first African American business is unknown, slaves captured from West Africa are believed to have established commercial enterprises as peddlers and skilled craftspeople as far back as the 17th century.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Washington became the most famous proponent of African American businesses.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] DuBois also commended business as a vehicle for African American advancement.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 2002, African American-owned businesses accounted for 1.2 million of the US's 23 million businesses.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] As of 2011, African American-owned businesses account for approximately two million US businesses.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Black-owned businesses experienced the largest growth in number of businesses among minorities from 2002 to 2011.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Twenty-five percent of Blacks had white-collar occupations (management, professional, and related fields) in 2000, compared with 33.6% of Americans overall.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 2001, over half of African American households of married couples earned $50,000 or more.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Although in the same year African Americans were over-represented among the nation's poor, this was directly related to the disproportionate percentage of African American families headed by single women; such families are collectively poorer, regardless of ethnicity.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 2006, the median earnings of African American men was more than Black and non-Black American women overall, and in all educational levels.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] At the same time, among American men, income disparities were significant; the median income of African American men was approximately 76 cents for every dollar of their European American counterparts, although the gap narrowed somewhat with a rise in educational level.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Overall, the median earnings of African American men were 72 cents for every dollar earned of their Asian American counterparts, and $1.17 for every dollar earned by Hispanic men.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] On the other hand, by 2006, among American women with post-secondary education, African American women have made significant advances; the median income of African American women was more than those of their Asian-, European- and Hispanic American counterparts with at least some college education.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The US public sector is the single most important source of employment for African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] During 2008–2010, 21.2% of all Black workers were public employees, compared with 16.3% of non-Black workers.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Both before and after the onset of the Great Recession, African Americans were 30% more likely than other workers to be employed in the public sector.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The public sector is also a critical source of decent-paying jobs for Black Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] For both men and women, the median wage earned by Black employees is significantly higher in the public sector than in other industries.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 1999, the median income of African American families was $33,255 compared to $53,356 of European Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In times of economic hardship for the nation, African Americans suffer disproportionately from job loss and underemployment, with the Black underclass being hardest hit.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The phrase "last hired and first fired" is reflected in the Bureau of Labor Statistics unemployment figures.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Nationwide, the October 2008 unemployment rate for African Americans was 11.1%, while the nationwide rate was 6.5%.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 2007, the average income for African Americans was approximately $34,000, compared to $55,000 for Whites.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African Americans experience a higher rate of unemployment than the general population.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The income gap between Black and White families is also significant.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 2005, employed Blacks earned 65% of the wages of Whites, down from 82% in 1975.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] *The New York Times* reported in 2006 that in Queens, New York, the median income among African American families exceeded that of White families, which the newspaper attributed to the growth in the number of two-parent Black families.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] It noted that Queens was the only county with more than 65,000 residents where that was true.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 2011, it was reported that 72% of Black babies were born to unwed mothers.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The poverty rate among single-parent Black families was 39.5% in 2005, according to Walter E.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Williams, while it was 9.9% among married-couple Black families.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Among White families, the respective rates were 26.4% and 6% in poverty.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Collectively, African Americans are more involved in the American political process than other minority groups in the United States, indicated by the highest level of voter registration and participation in elections among these groups in 2004.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African Americans also have the highest level of Congressional representation of any minority group in the US.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Homeownership in the US is the strongest indicator of financial stability and the primary asset most Americans use to generate wealth.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African Americans continue to lag behind other racial groups in homeownership.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In the first quarter of 2021, 45.1% of African Americans owned their homes, compared to 65.3% of all Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The African American homeownership rate has remained relatively flat since the 1970s despite an increase in anti-discrimination housing laws and protections.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The African American homeownership rate peaked in 2004 at 49.7%.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The average White high school drop-out still has a slightly better chance of owning a home than the average African American college graduate usually due to unfavorable debt-to-income ratios or credit scores among most African American college graduates.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Since 2000, fast-growing housing costs in most cities have made it even more difficult for the US African American homeownership rate to significantly grow and reach over 50% for the first time in history.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] From 2000 to 2022, the median home price in the US grew 160%, outpacing average annual household income growth in that same period, which only grew about 30%.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] South Carolina is the state with the most African American homeownership, with about 55% of African Americans owning their own homes.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Black people, who make up 12% of the total U.S. population, make up 32% of all people experiencing homelessness, according to the data.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Since the mid 20th century, a large majority of African Americans support the Democratic Party.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In the 2024 Presidential election, 86% of African American voters supported Democrat Kamala Harris, while 13% supported Republican Donald Trump.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Although there is an African American lobby in foreign policy, it has not had the impact that African American organizations have had in domestic policy.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Many African Americans were excluded from electoral politics in the decades following the end of Reconstruction.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The African American trend of voting for Democrats can be traced back to the 1930s during the Great Depression, when Franklin D.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal program provided economic relief to African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal coalition turned the Democratic Party into an organization of the working class and their liberal allies, regardless of region.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The African American vote became even more solidly Democratic when Democratic presidents John F.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Johnson pushed for civil rights legislation during the 1960s.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 1960, nearly a third of African Americans voted for Republican Richard Nixon.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Conservatism has been growing among African Americans, particularly since the 2020 Presidential election.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In the 2024 election, Trump secured a slightly larger share of the African American vote compared to his 2020 performance.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] "Lift Every Voice and Sing" is often referred to as the Black national anthem in the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 1919, the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) had dubbed it the "Negro national anthem" for its power in voicing a cry for liberation and affirmation for African-American people.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The majority of African Americans are Protestant, many of whom follow the historically Black churches.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The term Black church refers to churches which minister to predominantly African American congregations.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Black congregations were first established by freed slaves at the end of the 17th century, and later when slavery was abolished more African Americans were allowed to create a unique form of Christianity that was culturally influenced by African spiritual traditions.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] According to a 2007 survey, more than half of the African American population are part of the historically Black churches.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The largest Protestant denomination among African Americans is the Baptists, distributed mainly in four denominations, the largest being the National Baptist Convention, USA and the National Baptist Convention of America.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The second-largest is the Methodists, the largest organizations of which are the African Methodist Episcopal Church and the African Methodist Episcopal Zion Church.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Pentecostals are distributed among several different religious bodies, with the Church of God in Christ as the largest among them by far.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] About 16% of African American Christians are members of White Protestant communions; these denominations (which include the United Church of Christ) mostly have a 2–3% African American membership.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] There are also large numbers of Catholics, constituting 5% of the African American population.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Of the total number of Jehovah's Witnesses, 22% are Black.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Historically, between 15 and 30% of enslaved Africans brought to the Americas were Muslims, but most of these Africans were converted to Christianity during the era of American slavery.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Prominent members included activist Malcolm X and boxer Muhammad Ali.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Malcolm X is considered the first person to start the movement among African Americans towards mainstream Islam, after he left the Nation and made the pilgrimage to Mecca.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 1975, Warith Deen Mohammed, the son of Elijah Muhammad took control of the Nation after his father's death and guided the majority of its members to orthodox Islam.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African American Muslims constitute 20% of the total US Muslim population, the majority are Sunni or orthodox Muslims, some of these identify under the community of W.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The Nation of Islam led by Louis Farrakhan has a membership ranging from 20,000 to 50,000 members.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] There is also a small but growing group of African American Jews, making up less than 0.5% of African Americans or about 2% of the Jewish population in the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The majority of African-American Jews are Ashkenazi, while smaller numbers identify as Sephardi, Mizrahi, or other.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Many African-American Jews are affiliated with denominations such as the Reform, Conservative, Reconstructionist, or Orthodox branches of Judaism, but the majority identify as "Jews of no religion", commonly known as secular Jews.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] A significant number of people who identify themselves as "Black Jews" are affiliated with syncretic religious groups, largely the Black Hebrew Israelites, whose beliefs include the claim that African Americans are descended from the Biblical Israelites.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Jews of all races typically do not accept Black Hebrew Israelites as Jews, in part because they are usually not Jewish according to Jewish law, and in part because these groups are sometimes associated with antisemitism.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African-American Jews have criticized the Black Hebrew Israelites, regarding the movement as primarily composed of Black non-Jews who have appropriated Black-Jewish identity.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In the 2010s, confirmed atheists were less than one half of one percent, similar to numbers for Hispanics.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 2025, a Pew Research Center study found that, among Black Americans, Christian affiliation has declined in recent years.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The share of Black adults identifying as Christian fell from 85% in 2007 to 79% in 2014 and 73% in 2021, mirroring a broader decline in Christianity in the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] However, Black adults remain more likely than U.S. adults overall to identify as Christian (73% vs.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] By comparison, about half or fewer adults in other racial or ethnic groups report that religion is very important or that they pray daily, and even smaller shares attend services monthly.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Religiosity among Black Americans also varies by age.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] 39% of Black adults aged 65 and older describe themselves as very religious, compared with 21% of those under 30.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] This age pattern is similar to that observed among White and Hispanic Americans, although Black adults of all ages are more likely than other groups to describe themselves as very religious.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] According to a Gallup survey, 4.6% of Black or African Americans self-identified as LGBT in 2016, while the total portion of American adults in all ethnic groups identifying as LGBT was 4.1% in 2016.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African American women are more likely than African American men to openly identify as LGBT.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The life expectancy for Black men in 2008 was 70.8 years.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Life expectancy for Black women was 77.5 years in 2008.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 1900, when information on Black life expectancy started being collated, a Black man could expect to live to 32.5 years and a Black woman 33.5 years.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 1900, White men lived an average of 46.3 years and White women lived an average of 48.3 years.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African American life expectancy at birth is persistently five to seven years lower than European Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Black men have shorter lifespans than any other group in the US besides Native American men.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Black people have higher rates of obesity, diabetes, and hypertension than the US average.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] For adult Black men, the rate of obesity was 31.6% in 2010.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] For adult Black women, the rate of obesity was 41.2% in 2010.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African Americans have higher rates of mortality than any other racial or ethnic group for eight of the top ten causes of death.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 2013, among men, Black men had the highest rate of getting cancer, followed by White, Hispanic, Asian/Pacific Islander (A/PI), and American Indian/Alaska Native (AI/AN) men.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Among women, White women had the highest rate of getting cancer, followed by Black, Hispanic, Asian/Pacific Islander, and American Indian/Alaska Native women.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African Americans also have higher prevalence and incidence of Alzheimer's disease compared to the overall average.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Black women lead the nation in abortions.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] According to a 2022 report, Black women made up 40% of abortions despite making up 13% of the U.S. woman population.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African Americans are more likely than White Americans to die due to health-related problems developed by alcoholism.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Alcohol abuse is the main contributor to the top three causes of death among African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In December 2020, African Americans were less likely to be vaccinated against COVID-19 due to mistrust in the US medical system.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] From 2021 to 2022, there was an increase in African Americans who became vaccinated.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Still, in 2022, COVID-19 complications became the third leading cause of death for African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Violence is a major problem within the African American community.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] A report from the US Department of Justice states "In 2005, homicide victimization rates for Blacks were more than six times as high as the rates for Whites".
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The report also found that "94% of Black victims were killed by Blacks." Of the nearly 20,000 recorded US homicides in 2022, African Americans made up the majority of offenders and victims despite making up less than 15% of the population.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 2024, all of the five most dangerous US cities have a significant Black population and highly concerning Black-on-Black violent crime rate.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Black males age 15–44 are the only race/sex category for which homicide is a top-five cause of death.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Black women are three times more likely to be killed by an intimate partner than White women.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Black children are more than three times as likely to die due to parental abuse and neglect than White children.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, African Americans have higher rates of sexually transmitted infections (STIs) compared to Whites, with five times the rates of syphilis and chlamydia, and 7.5 times the rate of gonorrhea.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The disproportionately high incidence of HIV/AIDS among African Americans has been attributed to homophobic influences, lack of condom usage, and lack of proper healthcare.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The prevalence of HIV/AIDS among Black men is seven times higher than the prevalence for White men, and Black men are more than nine times as likely to die from HIV/AIDS-related illness than White men.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The prevalence of HIV/AIDS among Black women is 20 times higher than White women, and Black women are more than 15 times as likely to die from HIV/AIDS-related illness than White women.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African Americans have several barriers for accessing mental health services.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Counseling has been frowned upon and distant in utility and proximity to many people in the African American community.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 2004, a qualitative research study explored the disconnect with African Americans and mental health.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The study was conducted as a semi-structured discussion which allowed the focus group to express their opinions and life experiences.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] The results revealed a couple key variables that create barriers for many African American communities to seek mental health services such as the stigma, lack of four important necessities; trust, affordability, cultural understanding and impersonal services.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Historically, many African American communities did not seek counseling because religion was a part of the family values.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African Americans who have a faith background are more likely to seek prayer as a coping mechanism for mental issues rather than seeking professional mental health services.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 2015 a study concluded, African Americans with high value in religion are less likely to utilize mental health services compared to those who have low value in religion.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In the United States, counseling approaches are based on the experience of White Americans and do not fit within the African American culture.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] African American families tend to resolve concerns within the family, and it is viewed by the family as a strength.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] On the other hand, when African Americans seek counseling, they face a social backlash and are criticized.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] They may be labeled "crazy", viewed as weak, and their pride is diminished.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Because of this, many African Americans instead seek mentorship within communities they trust.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Terminology is another barrier in relation to African Americans and mental health.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] There is more stigma on the term *psychotherapy* versus counseling.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In one study, psychotherapy is associated with mental illness whereas counseling approaches problem-solving, guidance and help.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] More African Americans seek assistance when it is called counseling and not psychotherapy because it is more welcoming within the culture and community.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Counselors are encouraged to be aware of such barriers for the well-being of African American clients.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] Without cultural competency training in health care, many African Americans go unheard and misunderstood.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] In 2021, African Americans had the third highest suicide rate trailing American Indians/Alaska Natives and White Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] However, African Americans had the second highest increase of its suicide rate from 2011 to 2021, growing 58%.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p02] As of 2024, suicide is the second leading cause of death among African-Americans between the ages of 15 and 24, with Black men being four times more likely to kill themselves than Black women.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Recent studies of African Americans using genetic testing have found ancestry to vary by region and sex of ancestors.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] These studies found that on average, African Americans have 73.2–82.1% Sub-Saharan African, 16.7–24% European, and 0.8–1.2% Native American genetic ancestry, with large variation between individuals.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Commercial testing services have reported similar variation, with ranges from 0.6 to 2 percent Native American, 19 to 29 percent European, and 65 to 80 percent Sub-Saharan African ancestry.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] According to a genome-wide study by Bryc et al.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] (2009), the mixed ancestry of African Americans in varying ratios came about as the result of sexual contact between West/Central Africans (more frequently females) and Europeans (more frequently males).
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] This can be understood as being the result of enslaved African American females being raped by White males.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Consequently, the 365 African Americans in their sample have a genome-wide average of 78.1% West African ancestry and 18.5% European ancestry, with large variation among individuals (ranging from 99% to 1% West African ancestry).
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The West African ancestral component in African Americans is most similar to that in present-day speakers from the non-Bantu branches of the Niger-Congo family.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] (2014) observed that around 50% of the overall ancestry of African Americans traces comes from a population similar to the Niger-Congo-speaking Yoruba of southern Nigeria and southern Benin, reflecting the centrality of this West African region in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The next most frequent ancestral component found among African Americans was derived from Great Britain, in keeping with historical records.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] It constitutes a little over 10% of their overall ancestry and is most similar to the Northwest European ancestral component also carried by Barbadians.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] (2009) found a similar proportion of Yoruba-like ancestry in their African American samples, with a minority also drawn from Mandenka and Bantu populations.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Additionally, the researchers observed an average European ancestry of 21.9%, again with significant variation between individuals.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] (2009) note that populations from other parts of the continent may also constitute adequate proxies for the ancestors of some African American individuals; namely, ancestral populations from Guinea Bissau, Senegal and Sierra Leone in West Africa and Angola in Southern Africa.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] An individual African American person can have over fifteen African ethnic groups in their genetic makeup alone due to the slave trade covering such vast areas.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Altogether, genetic studies suggest that African Americans are a genetically diverse people.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] According to DNA analysis led in 2006 by Penn State geneticist Mark D.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] According to Shriver, around five percent of African Americans also have at least 12.5% Native American ancestry (equivalent to one Native American great-grandparent and their forebears).
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Research suggests that Native American ancestry among people who identify as African American is a result of relationships that occurred soon after slave ships arrived in the American colonies, and European ancestry is of more recent origin, often from the decades before the Civil War.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Africans bearing the E-V38 (E1b1a) likely traversed across the Sahara, from east to west, approximately 19,000 years ago.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] E-M2 (E1b1a1) likely originated in West Africa or Central Africa.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] According to a Y-DNA study by Sims et al.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] (2007), the majority (≈60%) of African Americans belong to various subclades of the E-M2 (E1b1a1, formerly E3a) paternal haplogroup.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] This is the most common genetic paternal lineage found today among West/Central African males and is also a signature of the historical Bantu migrations.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The next most frequent Y-DNA haplogroup observed among African Americans is the R1b clade, which around 15% of African Americans carry.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] This lineage is most common today among Northwestern European males.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The remaining African Americans mainly belong to the paternal haplogroup I (≈7%), which is also frequent in Northwestern Europe.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] According to an mtDNA study by Salas et al.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] (2005), the maternal lineages of African Americans are most similar to haplogroups that are today especially common in West Africa (>55%), followed closely by West-Central Africa and Southwestern Africa (<41%).
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The characteristic West African haplogroups L1b, L2b,c,d, and L3b,d and West-Central African haplogroups L1c and L3e in particular occur at high frequencies among African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] As with the paternal DNA of African Americans, contributions from other parts of the continent to their maternal gene pool are insignificant.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Formal political, economic and social discrimination against minorities has been present throughout American history.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Saito, Associate Professor of Sociology and American Studies & Ethnicity at the University of Southern California, writes, "Political rights have been circumscribed by race, class and gender since the founding of the United States, when the right to vote was restricted to White men of property.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Those who economically gained the most from slavery were the planter class, owners of large-scale plantations where large numbers of enslaved Africans were held captive and forced to produce crops to create wealth for a White elite.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Although they have gained a greater degree of social equality since the civil rights movement, African Americans have remained stagnant economically, which has hindered their ability to break into the middle class and beyond.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] As of 2020, the racial wealth gap between Whites and Blacks remains as large as it was in 1968, with the typical net worth of a White household equivalent to that of 11.5 Black households.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Despite this, African Americans have increased employment rates and gained representation in the highest levels of American government in the post–civil rights era.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] However, widespread racism remains an issue that continues to undermine the development of social status.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Economically, of all the racially Black ethnic groups on the globe, African Americans are the wealthiest and most successful, with one in every fifty African American families being millionaires.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] This equates in 2023 to approximately 1.79 million African American millionaires in the United States, which is more than the number of millionaires in any racially Black country, and many other countries, around the world.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] In the US, which has the largest per-capita prison population in the world, African Americans are overrepresented as the second-largest population of prison inmates (38%) in 2023, coming second to Whites, who made up 57% of the prison population.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] According to the National Registry of Exonerations, Blacks are roughly 7.5 times more likely to be wrongfully convicted of murder in the US than Whites.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] In 2012, the New York City Police Department detained people more than 500,000 times under the city's stop-and-frisk law.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Of the total detained, 55% were African-Americans, while Black people made up 20% of the city's population.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] African American males are more likely to be killed by police when compared to other races.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] This is one of the factors that led to the creation of the Black Lives Matter movement in 2013.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] According to *The Guardian*, "The specter of Karen persisted as Black Lives Matter protests and civil unrest spread around the country following Floyd's murder and reckonings with racism began to roil institutions, toppling careers as well as statues".
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] In the aftermath of the peak Black Lives Matter protests and widespread police reform efforts in the early 2020s, crime rates surged across the nation, especially in predominantly Black neighborhoods.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Many cities experienced near-record or record levels of violence and other criminal activity.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] As a result, numerous municipalities scaled back police reform initiatives and increased funding for law enforcement.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] After over 50 years, marriage rates for all Americans began to decline while divorce rates and out-of-wedlock births have climbed.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] These changes have been greatest among African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] After more than 70 years of racial parity Black marriage rates began to fall behind Whites.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Single-parent households have become most common, and according to US census figures released in January 2010, only 38% of Black children lived with both their parents.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] In 2021, statistics show that over 80% marriages in the African American ethnic group marry within their ethnic group.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Black children are overrepresented in the U.S. foster care system.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] In 2017, Black American children made up 14% of the children population but 22% of those in the foster care system.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Black American children are more than twice as likely to be placed in foster care than White American children.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The first ever anti-miscegenation law was passed by the Maryland General Assembly in 1691, criminalizing interracial marriage.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] In a speech in Charleston, Illinois in 1858, Abraham Lincoln stated, "I am not, nor ever have been in favor of making voters or jurors of negroes, nor of qualifying them to hold office, nor to intermarry with white people".
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] By the late 1800s, 38 US states had anti-miscegenation statutes.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] By 1924, the ban on interracial marriage was still in force in 29 states.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] While interracial marriage had been legal in California since 1948, in 1957 actor Sammy Davis Jr. faced a backlash for his involvement with White actress Kim Novak.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Harry Cohn, the president of Columbia Pictures, with whom Novak was under contract, gave in to his concerns that a racist backlash against the relationship could hurt the studio.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Davis briefly married Black dancer Loray White in 1958 to protect himself from mob violence.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Inebriated at the wedding ceremony, Davis despairingly said to his best friend, Arthur Silber Jr., "Why won't they let me live my life?" The couple never lived together, and commenced divorce proceedings in September 1958.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] In 1967 the law was ruled unconstitutional (via the 14th Amendment adopted in 1868) by the US Supreme Court in *Loving v.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] In 2008, Democrats overwhelmingly voted 70% against California Proposition 8, African Americans voted 58% in favor of it while 42% voted against Proposition 8.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] On May 9, 2012, Barack Obama, the first Black president, became the first US president to support same-sex marriage.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Since Obama's endorsement there has been a rapid growth in support for same-sex marriage among African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] As of 2012, 59% of African Americans support same-sex marriage, which is higher than support among the national average (53%) and White Americans (50%).
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Polls in North Carolina, Pennsylvania, Missouri, Maryland, Ohio, Florida, and Nevada have also shown an increase in support for same sex marriage among African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] On November 6, 2012, Maryland, Maine, and Washington all voted for approve of same-sex marriage, along with Minnesota rejecting a constitutional amendment banning same-sex marriage.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Exit polls in Maryland show about 50% of African Americans voted for same-sex marriage, showing a vast evolution among African Americans on the issue and was crucial in helping pass same-sex marriage in Maryland.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Black Americans hold far more conservative opinions on abortion, extramarital sex, and raising children out of wedlock than Democrats as a whole.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] On financial issues, however, African Americans are in line with Democrats, generally supporting a more progressive tax structure to provide more government spending on social services.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] African Americans have fought in every war in the history of the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The gains made by African Americans in the civil rights movement and in the Black Power movement not only obtained certain rights for African Americans but changed American society in far-reaching and fundamentally important ways.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Prior to the 1950s, Black Americans in the South were subject to de jure discrimination, or Jim Crow laws.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] They were often the victims of extreme cruelty and violence, sometimes resulting in deaths: by the post World War II era, African Americans became increasingly discontented with their long-standing inequality.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The civil rights movement marked an enormous change in American social, political, economic and civic life.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Over time, it has changed in fundamental ways the manner in which Blacks and Whites interact with and relate to one another.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Some activists and academics contend that American news media coverage of African American news, concerns, or dilemmas is inadequate, or that the news media present distorted images of African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Johnson founded Black Entertainment Television (BET), a network that targets young African Americans and urban audiences in the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Over the years, the network has aired such programming as rap and R&B music videos, urban-oriented movies and television series, and some public affairs programs.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] On Sunday mornings, BET would broadcast Christian programming; the network would also broadcast non-affiliated Christian programs during the early morning hours daily.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] According to Viacom, BET is now a global network that reaches households in the United States, Caribbean, Canada, and the United Kingdom.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The network has gone on to spawn several spin-off channels, including BET Her (originally launched as *BET on Jazz*).
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Another network targeting African Americans is TV One.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] TV One is owned by Urban One, founded and controlled by Catherine Hughes.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Urban One is one of the nation's largest radio broadcasting companies and the largest African American-owned radio broadcasting company in the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] In June 2009, NBC News launched a new website named TheGrio.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] It is the first African American video news site that focuses on underrepresented stories in existing national news.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] From their earliest presence in North America, African Americans have significantly contributed literature, art, agricultural skills, cuisine, clothing styles, music, language, and social and technological innovation to American culture.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The cultivation and use of many agricultural products in the United States, such as yams, peanuts, rice, okra, sorghum, grits, watermelon, indigo dyes, and cotton, can be traced to West African and African American influences.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Notable examples include George Washington Carver, who created nearly 500 products from peanuts, sweet potatoes, and pecans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Soul food is a variety of cuisine popular among African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] It is closely related to the cuisine of the Southern United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The descriptive terminology may have originated in the mid-1960s, when *soul* was a common definer used to describe African American culture (for example, soul music).
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] African Americans were the first peoples in the United States to make fried chicken, along with Scottish immigrants to the South.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Although the Scottish had been frying chicken before they emigrated, they lacked the spices and flavor that African Americans had used when preparing the meal.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The Scottish American settlers therefore adopted the African American method of seasoning chicken.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] However, fried chicken was generally a rare meal in the African American community and was usually reserved for special events or celebrations.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] African-American English is a variety (dialect, ethnolect, and sociolect) of American English, commonly spoken by urban working-class and largely bi-dialectal middle-class African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] It shares parts of its grammar and phonology with the Southern American English dialect.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] African American English differs from Standard American English (SAE) in certain pronunciation characteristics, tense usage, and grammatical structures, which were derived from West African languages (particularly those belonging to the Niger–Congo family).
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Virtually all habitual speakers of African American English can understand and communicate in Standard American English.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] As with all linguistic forms, AAVE's usage is influenced by various factors, including geographical, educational and socioeconomic background, as well as formality of setting.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Additionally, there are many literary uses of this variety of English, particularly in African American literature.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Other languages are spoken by specific sub-communities.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The Gullah language is an English-based creole language spoken mostly in the coastal regions of South Carolina and Georgia by the Gullah; an off-shoot of this is Afro-Seminole Creole spoken by Black Seminoles mostly now in Mexico and Brackettville, Texas.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Louisiana Creole is a French-based creole and spoken mostly in Louisiana.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] African-American names are part of the cultural traditions of African Americans, most of these cultural names having no connection to Africa but strictly an African American cultural practice that developed in the United States during enslavement.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] This new evidence became apparent by census records which show African Americans and White Americans, though they spoke the same language, chose to use different names even during times of enslavement, which is where and when the development of African American cultural names began.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Prior to this newer information, it was only thought that before the 1950s, and 1960s, most African-American names closely resembled those used within European-American culture.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Babies of that era were generally given a few common names, with children using nicknames to distinguish the various people with the same name.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] With the rise of 1960s civil rights movement, there was a dramatic increase in names of various origins.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] By the 1970s, and 1980s, it had become common among African Americans to invent new names for themselves, although many of these invented names took elements from popular existing names.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Prefixes such as La/Le, Da/De, Ra/Re and Ja/Je, and suffixes like -ique/iqua, -isha and -aun/-awn are common, as are inventive spellings for common names.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The book *Baby Names Now: From Classic to Cool—The Very Last Word on First Names* places the origins of "La" names in African-American culture in New Orleans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Even with the rise of inventive names, it is still common for African Americans to use biblical, historical, or traditional European names.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Daniel, Christopher, Michael, David, James, Joseph, and Matthew were thus among the most frequent names for African-American boys in 2013.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The name LaKeisha is typically considered American in origin but has elements that were drawn from both French and West/Central African roots.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Names such as LaTanisha, JaMarcus, DeAndre, and Shaniqua were created in the same way.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Punctuation marks are seen more often within African American names than other American names, such as the names Mo'nique and D'Andre.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] African American music is one of the most pervasive African American cultural influences in the United States today and is among the most dominant in mainstream popular music.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Hip-hop, R&B, funk, rock and roll, soul, blues, and other contemporary American musical forms originated in Black communities and evolved from other Black forms of music, including blues, doo-wop, barbershop, ragtime, bluegrass, jazz, and gospel music.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] African American-derived musical forms have also influenced and been incorporated into virtually every other popular music genre in the world, including country and techno.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] African Americans have also had an important role in American dance.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Jones, a prominent modern choreographer and dancer, has included historical African American themes in his work, particularly in the piece "Last Supper at Uncle Tom's Cabin/The Promised Land".
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Likewise, Alvin Ailey's artistic work, including his "Revelations" based on his experience growing up as an African American in the South during the 1930s, has had a significant influence on modern dance.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Another form of dance, stepping, is an African American tradition whose performance and competition has been formalized through the traditionally Black fraternities and sororities at universities.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Discussions of race and sports in the United States, where the two subjects have always been intertwined in American history, have focused to a great extent on African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Depending on the type of sport and performance level, African Americans are reported to be over- or under-represented.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] African Americans compose the highest percentage of the minority groups active at the professional level, but are among those who show the lowest participation overall.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] And though the list of African Americans in professional sports remains high, it only represents a small fraction of aspiring black athletes.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Many African American authors have written stories, poems, and essays influenced by their experiences as African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] African American literature is a major genre in American literature.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Famous examples include Langston Hughes, James Baldwin, Richard Wright, Zora Neale Hurston, Ralph Ellison, Nobel Prize winner Toni Morrison, and Maya Angelou.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] African American inventors have created many widely used devices in the world and have contributed to international innovation.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Norbert Rillieux created the technique for converting sugar cane juice into white sugar crystals.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Moreover, Rillieux left Louisiana in 1854 and went to France, where he spent ten years working with the Champollions deciphering Egyptian hieroglyphics from the Rosetta Stone.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Most slave inventors were nameless, such as the slave owned by the Confederate President Jefferson Davis who designed the ship propeller used by the Confederate navy.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] By 1913, over 1,000 inventions were patented by Black Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Among the most notable inventors were Jan Matzeliger, who developed the first machine to mass-produce shoes, and Elijah McCoy, who invented automatic lubrication devices for steam engines.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Granville Woods had 35 patents to improve electric railway systems, including the first system to allow moving trains to communicate.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Morgan developed the first automatic traffic signal and gas mask.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Lewis Howard Latimer invented an improvement for the incandescent light bulb.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] More recent inventors include Frederick McKinley Jones, who invented the movable refrigeration unit for food transport in trucks and trains.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Lloyd Quarterman worked with six other Black scientists on the creation of the atomic bomb (code named the Manhattan Project) and helped develop the first nuclear reactor.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] As part of the preservation of their culture, African Americans have continuously launched their own publications and publishing houses, such as Robert Sengstacke Abbott, founder of the Chicago Defender newspaper, and Carter G.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Woodson, the founder of Black History Month who spent over thirty years documenting and publishing African American history in journals and books.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The Johnson Publishing Company, founded by John H.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Johnson in 1942, is a National Historic Landmark.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The term *African American* was popularized by Jesse Jackson in the 1980s, although there are recorded uses from the 18th and 19th centuries, for example, in post-emancipation holidays and conferences.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Earlier terms also used to describe Americans of African ancestry referred more to skin color than to ancestry.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Other terms (such as *colored*, *person of color*, or *negro*) were included in the wording of various laws and legal decisions which some thought were being used as tools of White supremacy and oppression.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] A 16-page pamphlet entitled "A Sermon on the Capture of Lord Cornwallis" is notable for the attribution of its authorship to "An *African American*".
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Published in 1782, the book's use of this phrase predates any other yet identified by more than 50 years.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] In the 1980s, the term *African American* was advanced to give descendants of American slaves, and other American Blacks who lived through the slavery era, a heritage and a cultural base.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The term was popularized in Black communities around the country via word of mouth and ultimately received mainstream use after Jesse Jackson's use in 1988.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Subsequently, major media outlets adopted it.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Surveys in the 1990s and the first decade of the 21st century showed that the majority of Black Americans had no preference for *African American* versus *Black American*, although they had a slight preference for the latter in personal settings and the former in more formal settings.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] By 2021, according to polling from Gallup, 58% of Black Americans expressed no preference for what their group should be called, with 17% each preferring *Black* and *African-American*.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] In 2023, the government released a new more detailed breakdown due to the rise in racially Black immigration into the US, listing African American as a compound termed ethnicity, distinguished from other racially Black ethnicities such as Nigerian, Jamaican etc.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The term *African American* embraces pan-Africanism as earlier enunciated by prominent African thinkers such as Marcus Garvey, W.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The term *Afro-Usonian*, and variations of such, are more rarely used.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] In preparation for the 2010 US census, a marketing and outreach plan called *2010 Census Integrated Communications Campaign Plan* (ICC) recognized and defined African Americans as Black people born in the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] From the ICC perspective, African Americans are one of three groups of Black people in the United States: African Americans, Black Africans, and Afro-Caribbeans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The ICC plan was to reach the three groups by acknowledging that each group has its own sense of community that is based on geography and ethnicity.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The best way to market the census process toward any of the three groups is to reach them through their own unique communication channels and not treat the entire Black population of the US as though they are all African Americans with a single ethnic and geographical background.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Historically, "race mixing" between Black and White people was taboo in the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] So-called anti-miscegenation laws, barring Blacks and Whites from marrying or having sex, were established in colonial America as early as 1691, and endured in many Southern states until the Supreme Court ruled them unconstitutional in *Loving v.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The taboo among American Whites surrounding White-Black relations is a historical consequence of the oppression and racial segregation of African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Harvard University historian Henry Louis Gates Jr. wrote in 2009 that "African Americans...are a racially mixed or mulatto people—deeply and overwhelmingly so".
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] After the Emancipation Proclamation, Chinese American men married African American women in high proportions to their total marriage numbers due to few Chinese American women being in the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] African slaves and their descendants have also had a history of cultural exchange and intermarriage with Native Americans, although they did not necessarily retain social, cultural or linguistic ties to Native peoples.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] There are also increasing intermarriages and offspring between non-Hispanic Blacks and Hispanics of any race, especially between Puerto Ricans and African Americans.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Racially mixed marriages have become increasingly accepted in the United States since the civil rights movement.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] A Gallup poll conducted in 2013 found that 84% of Whites and 96% of Blacks approved of interracial marriage, and 87% overall.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Black men are more than twice as likely to date and marry interracially than Black women.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] At the end of World War II, some African American military men stationed in Asia and Europe impregnated local non-Black women, resulting in the birth of thousands of mixed-race children called "Brown Babies".
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Some of these families later immigrated to the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] However, some mixed-race children, especially in Japan, were placed in orphanages due to social stigmas associated with half-Black fatherless children in the 1950s.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Author Debra Dickerson has argued that the term *Black* should refer strictly to the descendants of Africans who were brought to America as slaves, and not to the sons and daughters of Black immigrants who lack that ancestry.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Thus, under her definition, President Barack Obama, who is the son of a Kenyan, is not Black.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] "Lumping us all together", Dickerson wrote, "erases the significance of slavery and continuing racism while giving the appearance of progress." Similar comments have been made concerning Kamala Harris, the daughter of a Jamaican immigrant, who was elected vice president in 2020.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The American Descendants of Slavery (ADOS) movement coalesces around this view, arguing that Black descendants of American slavery deserve a separate ethnic category that distinguishes them from other Black groups in the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Their terminology has gained popularity in some circles, but others have criticized the movement for a perceived bias against (especially poor and Black) immigrants, and for its often inflammatory rhetoric.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Politicians such as Obama and Harris have received especially pointed criticism from the movement, as neither are ADOS and have spoken out at times against policies specific to them.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Most notably, Malcolm X and Kwame Ture expressed similar views that African Americans are Africans who "happen to be in America", and should not claim or identify as being American if they are fighting for Black (New Afrikan) liberation.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Historically, this is due to the enslavement of Africans during the transatlantic slave trade, ongoing anti-Black violence, and structural racism in countries like the United States.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Before the independence of the Thirteen Colonies until the abolition of slavery in 1865, an African American slave was commonly known as a *negro*.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] *Free negro* was the legal status in the territory of an African American person who was not enslaved.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The term was used until the second quarter of the 20th century, when it was considered outmoded – although it was retained in the name of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) – and generally gave way again to the exclusive use of *negro*.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] By the 1940s, the term was commonly capitalized (*Negro*); but by the mid-1960s, it was considered disparaging.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] By the end of the 20th century, *negro* had come to be considered inappropriate and was rarely used and perceived as a pejorative.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The term is rarely used by younger Black people, but remained in use by many older African Americans who had grown up with the term, particularly in the Southern US.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The term remains in use in some contexts, such as the United Negro College Fund, an American philanthropic organization.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] There are many other deliberately insulting terms, many of which were in common use (e.g., *nigger*), but had become unacceptable in normal discourse before the end of the 20th century.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] One exception is the use, among the Black community, of the slur *nigger* rendered as *nigga*, representing the pronunciation of the word in African American English.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] This usage has been popularized by American rap and hip-hop music cultures and is used as part of an in-group lexicon and speech.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] It is not necessarily derogatory and, when used among Black people, the word is often used to mean "homie" or "friend".
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] Acceptance of intra-group usage of the word *nigga* is still debated, although it has established a foothold among younger generations.
[src:governor-of-virginia/african-americans-p03] The NAACP denounces the use of both *nigga* and *nigger*.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] He is the oldest of five sons to Albert Sr. and Genevieve Pilgrim-Bryan.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] He grew up in the Savan neighborhood of Charlotte Amalie, the territory's capital.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Dunstan's Episcopal High School in 1985.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Bryan earned his BA in economics from Wittenberg University in 1989.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] He received a Master of Business Administration from the University of the Virgin Islands in 2003.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] In 2007, Governor John de Jongh appointed him to be Commissioner of the Virgin Islands Department of Labor.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] When de Jongh's term ended in 2015, Bryan returned to the private sector.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] He was CEO and President of Aabra Group, a consulting firm, and Master Strategies, a recruiting firm.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] He also was executive director of the Virgin Islands chapter of Junior Achievement.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] In April 2018, Bryan officially announced his candidacy for governor and chose Tregenza Roach as his running mate.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] They won the August 4 Democratic primary with 39.23% of the vote, defeating former Finance commissioner Angel E.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Dawson Jr. and former Senator Allison "Allie" Petrus.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] The team campaigned on restoring trust to government, stabilizing the economy, modernizing infrastructure, education, healthcare, reducing crime and poverty, affordable housing, and attracting rum distilleries to rescue GERS.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Bryan led the 2018 general election with 38% of the vote and defeated incumbent governor Kenneth Mapp in a runoff with over 55% of the vote.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] He is the second Democrat to unseat a sitting governor since Charles W.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Bryan launched his reelection bid on May 11, 2022.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] In the August 6 primary, he defeated Kent Bernier Sr. with 65.04% of the vote.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] He won the November 8 general election, defeating Senator Kurt Vialet and two other candidates with 56% of the vote.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Bryan was sworn in as the 9th governor of the United States Virgin Islands by Rhys Hodge, Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of the Virgin Islands on January 7, 2019, at David Monsanto Bandstand, which was built by his grandfather Ulric “Sappy” Pilgrim in Emancipation Gardens on St.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Before the ceremony, Bryan and his family attended an inaugural Mass at Saints Peter and Paul Cathedral.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] The inauguration proceed with military parades and inaugural balls held on all three islands.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Upon assuming office, Bryan announced his senior staff and pledged to fill his cabinet within 90 days.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Early administrative actions included securing a FEMA extension for the STEP hurricane recovery program and declaring a mental healthcare state of emergency due to a territorial shortage of psychiatrists.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] In 2019, Bryan cleared all outstanding government debt to the Virgin Islands Water & Power Authority (WAPA) and purchased four new generators to combat rolling blackouts.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] In 2021, he filed suit to block legislation reducing the WAPA board's size, and in April 2024 declared a state of emergency for WAPA following widespread outages.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] In October 2022, Bryan announced the V.I.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] On January 19, 2023, Bryan signed the Equality Act prohibiting discrimination based on sexual orientation or gender identity, and in 2024 introduced legislation allowing individuals to change their gender on identifying documents.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Bryan declared a state of emergency on March 13, 2020, implementing business closures and travel testing requirements.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] In-person schooling was suspended for the remainder of the 2019–2020 school year.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] During his tenure as governor, Bryan faced significant scrutiny regarding his administration's handling of litigation involving Jeffrey Epstein and the territory's historical financial relationship with Epstein's entities.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] According to unsealed federal court filings from June 2023, Epstein's companies—specifically Southern Trust Company and Financial Trust Company—were granted approximately $300 million in tax benefits by the Virgin Islands government between 1999 and 2018.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] The filings detailed that $219.8 million in benefits were awarded between 1999 and 2012, followed by an additional $80.6 million from 2013 to 2018.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Bryan concurrently served as the Commissioner of the Virgin Islands Department of Labor and as the Chairman of the Virgin Islands Economic Development Authority (EDA) Board from 2007 to 2015, the body responsible for overseeing the certification of these tax incentives.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Bryan's administration oversaw the departure of three successive Attorneys General during the height of the territory's litigation against Epstein's estate and his financial partners.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] In federal court filings, JPMorgan Chase pursued an "unclean hands" defense, alleging that the USVI government actively harbored and shielded Epstein for two decades.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] The bank's filings differentiated between individuals connected to separate administrations, noting that Cecile de Jongh, wife of former Governor John de Jongh, had served as the office manager for Epstein's Southern Trust Company for eight years.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] The filings further alleged that the Governor's former wife, Yolanda Bryan, had been involved in efforts to procure student visas for individuals associated with Epstein during Bryan's tenure.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Beyond the Epstein litigation, Bryan's administration has faced separate ethical and legal challenges regarding local procurement and campaign finance.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] In 2020, the Bryan administration was criticized for attempting to award a $1 million no-bid contract for COVID-19 contact tracing to Avera Tech, a startup co-founded by his daughter, Aliyah Bryan, and a former campaign intern.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Senators criticized the Health Department for circumventing standard procurement processes, and the contract was ultimately dropped following public outcry and a legislative probe.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] In 2023, the Elections System of the Virgin Islands fined the Bryan-Roach campaign $2,000 for holding an illegal "international virtual fundraiser" in September 2022.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] The event featured the Prime Minister of Dominica, Roosevelt Skerrit, as a "special guest," violating Title 18 of the V.I.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Code, which prohibits foreign officials from fundraising or endorsing U.S. candidates.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] In November 2023, Bryan filed for divorce from his wife, Yolanda Bryan, and successfully petitioned the V.I.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Superior Court to seal the case in its entirety.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] The decision to remove case ST-2023-DI-00113 from the public docket faced scrutiny because the presiding judge was up for reappointment to the bench by the Governor in 2024.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Bryan and his wife, Yolanda Cabodevilla, have been married since 1998.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] They have two daughters, Aliyah and Sumuyah.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] Bryan lives in Government House in Christiansted on St.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albert-bryan-jr] In March 2019, the West Indian Company authorized monthly rent payments of $3,500 for a condo where Bryan would stay while on St.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] Harrison is the first governor of Virginia to have been born in the 20th century.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] Harrison was born in Alberta, Virginia, the son of Albertis Sydney Harrison and Lizzie, (née Goodrich).
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] He has been widely reported as related to Benjamin Harrison V who signed the Declaration of Independence and two United States presidents, William Henry Harrison and Benjamin Harrison, the 9th and 23rd Presidents, however before his death, he found this to be false.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] He received a Bachelor of Laws degree from the University of Virginia Law School in 1928.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] Harrison married Lacey Virginia Barkley in 1930.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] They had two children: Antoinette H Jamison and Albertis S.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] Harrison III; and 6 grandchildren: Joseph D.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] Goodrich Harrison, Monica Harrison Kopf, Virginia Lacey Jamison, and James Carper Jamison II.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] Harrison went into legal practice in Lawrenceville, Virginia, where he became town attorney, before being elected commonwealth's attorney of Brunswick County.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] He was elected to the Senate of Virginia in 1947.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] He served there for ten years, before being elected Attorney General of Virginia in 1957.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] Harrison resigned as attorney general in April 1961 to run for governor, winning election that November with 63.84% of the vote, defeating Republican H.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] His administration increased educational financing for new schools and laboratories and raised teachers' pay.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] He promoted the development of state-supported colleges and technical schools as well as improved vocational training.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] He helped to modernize state banking laws to attract investment and accelerated highway construction.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] He sat on the Virginia Supreme Court of Appeals, later renamed the Supreme Court of Virginia, from 1968 to 1981.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] In 1968 he chaired the Commission on Constitutional Revision that drafted the 1971 Constitution of Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] As Attorney General, Harrison was responsible for defending the state's resistance to school integration, as part of the Massive Resistance strategy endorsed and led by the state's political leader, United States Senator Harry F.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] Part of Massive Resistance involved the closing of public schools in various Virginia cities and counties to prevent racially integrated classrooms.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] County School Board of Prince Edward County* (1952) was one of the companion cases to *Brown v.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] Board of Education* (1954), but the Supreme Court had left enforcement to the local federal district judge.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] Moreover, the Gray Commission of Byrd loyalists had recommended passage of various laws to avoid or delay integration.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] After opinions by the Virginia Supreme Court on January 19, 1959, as well as a three-judge federal panel overturned much of the new Virginia legislation, Governor J.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] Lindsay Almond (previously attorney general) and Harrison decided not to defy those courts and allowed schools in Arlington and Norfolk to reopen.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] However the schools in Prince Edward County closed in 1958 and did not reopen until 1963, as white students used tuition grants to attend a private segregation academy at state expense, while black students were left to volunteer efforts.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] Other problematic school closures, ultimately opened pursuant to federal court orders included those in Albemarle, Warren County and later New Kent County (the subject of the 1968 Supreme Court decision in *Green v.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] County School Board of New Kent County* (1968).
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] Harrison told the board to comply unless they were willing to risk prosecution.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] By this time, he, like a number of other Byrd Democrats, had concluded that obstinate resistance to integration could not continue.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] Another aspect of Massive Resistance involved new laws regulating attorney ethics, designed to attack practices of the NAACP, which was pursuing the desegregation actions.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] Supreme Court deferred to an upcoming decision of the Virginia Supreme Court about those new ethics rules in *Harrison v.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] NAACP* (1959), but the case came before it twice more in *NAACP v.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] Button* (1963) (which was reargued after Harrison resigned as attorney general to run for governor, and which Virginia lost under attorney general Robert Young Button.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] Harrison died of a heart attack at his home in Lawrenceville on January 23, 1995.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] He is buried in Oakwood Cemetery in Lawrenceville, Virginia.
[src:governor-of-virginia/albertis-harrison] The courthouse in Lawrenceville is named in his honor.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] Major-General **Alexander Spotswood** (12 December 1676 – 7 June 1740) was a British army officer, explorer and colonial administrator who served as the governor of Virginia from 1710 to 1722.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] After an unsatisfactory military career, in 1710 he was appointed as Virginia's governor, a post he held for twelve years.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] During that period, Spotswood engaged in the exploration of the territories beyond the western border, of which he was the first to see the economic potentials.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] As the governor of Virginia, Spotswood's first preoccupation was to make sea routes safe and fight against the pirates.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] After a long effort, the famous pirate Blackbeard was hunted down and killed in 1718.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] In addition, Spotswood promoted the economic growth of the colony by founding the metallurgical settlements of Germanna; introduced the juridical instrument of habeas corpus; and introduced the rules for the commercial relations with Native Americans and those for the tobacco export trade.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] His tenure was characterised by a growing conflict with the Virginian political classes, which ended with his removal from office.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] Years later, between 1730 and 1739, Spotswood was the Deputy Postmaster General of British America and, with his young friend Benjamin Franklin, extended the postal service network north of Williamsburg and improved its efficiency.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] At the outbreak of the War of Jenkins' Ear, Spotswood was called back into army service.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] Promoted to major general, he was put in command of the colonial troops stationed in America with the task of preparing a military action against the Spanish stronghold of Cartagena de Indias, but, in Annapolis, where he was to consult with the local governors, he died suddenly in 1740.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] Alexander Spotswood was born in Tangier, a city on the African shore of the Strait of Gibraltar, in 1676.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] 1638 – December 1709), the daughter of the Rev.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] 1655), who gave him an only son, Alexander.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] Alexander's older half-brother (by his mother's first marriage to George Elliott) was Roger Elliott, who became one of the first governors of Gibraltar.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] Both parents had Scottish origins, and the father, although economically ruined, could boast an illustrious lineage as a direct descendant of Robert the Bruce.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] His family had ancient baronial origins and had enjoyed great prestige until the time of the English Revolution.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] There had been illustrious Spotswoods, such as judge Sir Robert Spottiswoode (Alexander's grandfather) and Archbishop John Spottiswoode.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] In 1684, following attacks of native Berber troops under the guide of governor Ali ben Abdallah, the city of Tangier was evacuated and the Spotswood family returned to England, where the father died in 1688.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] In May 1693, at the age of sixteen, Spotswood enlisted in the English Army, the army of the Kingdom of England, with the rank of Ensign in the Earl of Bath's Regiment of Foot.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] He served first in Ireland and then in the Flanders.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] Over the years, distinguishing himself for skill, courage and intelligence, he climbed the military hierarchy to the rank of lieutenant colonel.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] The War of Spanish Succession broke out in 1701.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] The main European powers fought each other throughout the following decade.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough, was in command of the English army stationed in central Europe.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] Alexander Spotswood was part of it as deputy quartermaster general.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] The troops remained quartered along the River Rhine for three years for the protection of the Netherlands.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] Marlborough's army descended into Bavaria In 1704, taking the Franco-Bavarian forces by surprise.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] The Battle of Blenheim took place on August 13 and ended in a major British victory.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] During the battle Spotswood was severely wounded in the chest during a heavy artillery attack.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] Medicated on the battlefield, he was then sent to London to convalesce.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] He survived and kept the cannonball, which he used to show his friends and guests.
[src:governor-of-virginia/alexander-spotswood] He returned to the Flanders almost two years later.
